Title: a river enchanted
Author: rebecca ross
review: The book was a great find, and I really enjoyed reading it. The summary doesn't do justice to the book's actual plot. This story wasn't just about JacThe book was a great find, and I really enjoyed reading it. The summary doesn't do justice to the book's actual plot. This story wasn't just about Jack; it was about the many people in the town whose lives and relationships were intertwined. One thing I really loved about this story was the relationship between Torin and Sidra. Sometimes, you can tell which character's story an author is really passionate about telling. Their relationship on the paper felt real and tangible, and they had very realistic emotions and fleshed-out dialogues.However, since Jack is the main character in this novel, I was terribly disappointed in the way he was regarded as a side character. His romance with Adaira felt very frustrating because I genuinely couldn't feel the chemistry between the characters. I felt like the author just shoved the enemies-to-lovers trope in our faces. It didn't feel real or fleshed out properly, and I kept comparing their relationship to that of Torin and Sidra (which left me wanting more). In fact, at the end, I was a bit relieved when Adaira decided to leave Jack to remain in the west (or east?) I forgot which side they were on.In the end, I will definitely get a paper copy of this book to keep at home. It was a very warm, cozy and slow (EMPHASIS on SLOW) read....more

review: **spoiler alert** I have never been a huge Britney fan (nor have I hated her). I off and on found her annoying because she was so pretty and peppy so**spoiler alert** I have never been a huge Britney fan (nor have I hated her). I off and on found her annoying because she was so pretty and peppy so I was so surprised to be able to relate to her. The abuse she went through, the dysfunctional narcissistic family, the relationship with her sister, and the pregnancy loss I understood and felt for her. (Minus the fame and money) I did feel bad about her being so obviously exploited and what the media said was horrible. But how she was able to get through it and get out of the conservatorship, which FYI is only $1,000 for her family to muzzle her with. The book was just eye opening and sad how many who are in the spotlight don't seem to have any real foundation, especially child stars. I wish her much happiness and GOOD adventures to come in her life. I hope her freedom finally allows her to heal.FYI I listened to the version on Audible, which really helped because I have ADHD. review: When I started reading this book, I was amazed about the principles, examples, insights, tips and instructions presented through each chapter.I have bWhen I started reading this book, I was amazed about the principles, examples, insights, tips and instructions presented through each chapter.I have been into habits and behavior change for a while, I read "The Power of Habit" and many other books that covers this subject.I tired to combine as many approaches, techniques and principles that I could ever gather form every where.I recorded some triumphs and eliminated some negative or bad habits, however, I'm still struggling with some negative habits that are still embedded in my nervous system and body. review: This book taunted me from the bookshelf for well over a year before I was finally ready to pull it down and begin following the Bains' stories. I'd beThis book taunted me from the bookshelf for well over a year before I was finally ready to pull it down and begin following the Bains' stories. I'd been waiting until I felt ready to read what, from the reviews, was sure to be a heart-wrenching and depressing story of an impoverished and alcoholic mother and her young son.Perhaps my expectations were set too high, but I never really connected with anyone in this book. I didn't feel any of the characters were particularly redeeming, and I struggled to get through this one. The second half of the book, especially, left me wanting more from the story. I'm not sure exactly what "more" would have looked like, but I just longed for something different.The book certainly has a few tragic moments that delivered on what many other reviews say it will, but overall it left me feeling a bit ambivalent and just wasn't my cup of tea....more

The beautiful writing in this book caught me by wonderful surprise time and again. I came to this story unfamiliar the author and did not expect to be so entirely blown away by the elegant prose. Only a poet could write with such grace!A tumultuous, and at times heart-wrenching, story of poor Vietnamese immigrants to the US offers the perfect juxtaposition to the graceful writing. And so many observations the author makes, like the quote below, are worth taking a moment to digest."Too much joy, I swear, is lost in our desperation to keep it."This is one of those books that I will recommend to everyone while being sure to keep my own copy on the bookshelf so I can stare at the beautiful cover and revisit the story from time to time. Title: the overstory
Author: richard powers
review: **A few minor spoilers ahead**The Overstory reads like poetry spoken by nature. The author must certainly have spent time practicing and becoming the**A few minor spoilers ahead**The Overstory reads like poetry spoken by nature. The author must certainly have spent time practicing and becoming the voice of the natural world.What struck me most was how the natural world (and, specifically, trees) approach time. The first 150 pages or so of the book introduce us to nine main characters, my favorite definitely being Patricia Westerford. In many of their stories, we journey through family histories that go back over 100 years. Using tree-like transitions to describe the passage of time, we're able to jump decades into the future, what should feel like a significant leap, in the calming, nurturing words of nature, through seasons and tree lifecycles.After being introduced to the main characters, their journeys begin slowly connecting. In short, many of them become eco-activists, hoping to save the three percent of old growth forest left in the country, most of which lies in the Pacific Northwest, from deforestation.While I enjoyed all of the characters, I learned the most from Patricia. A pioneering forestry scientist, she makes remarkable discoveries as a young researcher and decides to publish her findings that trees communicate with each other in many different ways. Post publication, the natural science community completely dismisses her, some even suggesting she's become unhinged. She retreats into a largely lonely life. Over the years that follow, her discoveries are vindicated by additional data, which leads to the publication of her book.(Insert book name that I can't remember)becomes *the* definitive book on trees. She then settles into her role as a researcher and occasional public speaker, bringing much greater public awareness to forests and trees. I learned so much from her character's reverence of the natural world.I have a strong feeling this will be one of those books I become nostalgic for when I see it on the bookshelf in years to come. I absolutely loved it....more

Title: the great believers
Author: rebecca makkai
review: 3.5 stars, rounded up.In The Great Believers, we follow Yale as he procures an immensely valuable art exhibit for his museum while the AIDS crisis rav3.5 stars, rounded up.In The Great Believers, we follow Yale as he procures an immensely valuable art exhibit for his museum while the AIDS crisis ravages his tight-knit gay community in 1980s Chicago. The story alternates between this and Fiona, who is Yale's friend's sister, some thirty years later as she searches Paris for her estranged daughter.I absolutely loved the parts of this story set in 1980s Chicago. The author successfully depicts the devastating loss, hopelessness, and discrimination facing the gay community as the AIDS epidemic unfolds. I commend her for bringing this story to a new generation of readers (myself included) who did not experience the AIDS crisis firsthand.My struggle with this book came with the present-day search for Fiona's long lost adult daughter. This part of the story just didn't grab my attention. I so loved being in Yale's world, and, though the two storylines eventually connect, I couldn't help but wish the entire novel had been set in 1980s Chicago. I simply didn't care as much about Fiona's storyline in comparison to Yale's....more

Title: the seven year slip
Author: ashley poston
review: This book was my first 5 star read of 2023.I fell in love with Clementine and Iwan. I found myself smiling through most of the book. I was so intriguThis book was my first 5 star read of 2023.I fell in love with Clementine and Iwan. I found myself smiling through most of the book. I was so intrigued by the dual timelines. It was an absolute blast to get taken on a journey back and forth from seven years prior to current day. Ashley Poston did this so well! I've recently read a couple of other books that try to have two different timelines going at the same time and neither worked, but it Ashley accomplished it perfectly in The Seven Year Slip.I love that the magic of the apartment is never explained. It was done in a way that didn't leave you curious, just pleasantly surprised each time travel.I've heard people criticize some of the characters' decisions and had to laugh. Like, do you want perfect people or real people? I prefer characters to be realistic and the fact that they sometimes make choices you disagree with with an outside perspective is what makes the book amazing! Title: everything, everything
Author: nicola yoon
review: I loved this book! It made me really open my eyes to the fact that love can blind us. Sometimes I feel like I am being held captive when my mother makI loved this book! It made me really open my eyes to the fact that love can blind us. Sometimes I feel like I am being held captive when my mother makes me stay home one night. I cannot imagine being isolated from the world for so long. Having no memories, experiences or stories to tell would be agonizing. Olly entering her life gave her excitement and hope. If I were in her shoes i would have done the same thing, and I hope I would have a nurse willing to help me out. I think it is very sacrificial of Carla allowing Olly into the house because she knows what the repercussions could be, but it shows she truly loves and cares for Madeline. That gave me, as a reader, a personal favorite character and hope for all of the characters. I loved the way all of the characters were portrayed and the desperation that Madeline's mother has for her is very obvious, almost as obvious as Madeline's hunger for freedom. The want for freedom is easy to relate to as a teen. The extreme isolation she faces makes me appreciate the amount of freedom I actually have. I loved this book and thing it is a great read if you want to feel free and willing....more

Title: to kill a kingdom
Author: alexandra christo
review: **spoiler alert** This was an average read, nothing too exciting, therefore I gave it three stars. This book is a retelling of the little mermaid and**spoiler alert** This was an average read, nothing too exciting, therefore I gave it three stars. This book is a retelling of the little mermaid and follows the perspectives of a siren and a prince as their problems entwine.What I likedI liked how Lira was ruthless, yet caring and i enjoyed reading about her past and the hatred towards her mother.I loved Lira's planning to get back to her throne and overthrow the queen.Lira attitude was well written and she felt very real, there was never a time of sudden mood changes in this book and I loved her witty comebacks.What I didn't likeElian's character reminded me too much of the Riden from Daughter of the Pirate King. Elian was a weird character and I just couldn't place what he wanted and how he was feeling even though we did get his perspective. He just wasn't interesting enough.Even though he is inspired by the little mermaid, there is very little connection between the two. Lira isn't a pretty mermaid, Elian is 'the' prince. The story isn't right either so I don't understand why people are comparing the two.The story itself wasn't exciting and kind of dull, it mostly focused on finding the gem and Lira and Elian using each other.The relationship was also not right. At one point they don't like each other and the next Lira is asking him to kiss her. I just didn't build up.There also wasn't a heap of actionThe endingThe ending was pretty cool, Lira got the courage to overthrow her mother, Elian realised his deep love for Lira. A whole heap of fighting and then a happy ending. Not much....more

Title: legendary
Author: stephanie garber
review: **spoiler alert** I have read 70 books and only twice have I given all the books in the series such a high rating. I absolutely adore this book. It is**spoiler alert** I have read 70 books and only twice have I given all the books in the series such a high rating. I absolutely adore this book. It is told from Tella's perspective and honestly, I enjoyed reading from her p.o.v more than Scarlett's. This is only because I found Tella more independent and I am such a sucker for strong female leads.Even though I enjoyed the world in 'Caraval' better, it wasn't that bad here because I would have liked to see more of the magic and the wonders. I believe the last book was more magical because we were just being introduced to 'Caraval' and Stephanie Garber had to put in a little more effort to impress the readers but in this book, we were already quite familiar with it.The book wasn't that heavy on romance but it was definitely one of the key points in the book. Jacks was just perfect and Dante was not my favourite, even though they sort of had the same personality in a way. Jacks was a new character in the book and even before I knew him as the prince of hearts, I fell in love with him in the carriage. He was beautifully arrogant. Dante, I can't even talk about him. I hated him from the very start to the very end. I felt as though Tella could do much better and he wasn't even charming as others are making him, he was just annoying. I was team Jella from the start and am still shipping Jacks and Tella together.The ending was perfect, it was magnificent and even better than the last book. It was so clean and smooth, I think it may be the best ending I have ever read. Legend was revealed and Tella admitted to having fallen in love with him (I hope this changes in the next book). It was a flawless reveal, not exciting as it was kinda obvious, but still perfect.Scarlett and Julian were on a rocky boat in their relationship and Scarlett even started looking for her last fiancé. I just really hope she doesn't end up with Julian, their relationship was only sweet in 'Caraval'. I am dying to know if Julian is actually real with her or not or if she will end up finding a person better. Julian kept on lying and was just really untrustworthy, especially because he ended up being 'someones' brother.Overall, I loved the characters in this book and I adore Tella, even more than Scarlett. The world was mesmerising. I am excited to read the last book in the trilogy....more

Title: the mime order
Author: samantha shannon
review: **spoiler alert** I gave The Mime Order three stars because, like the other book, it was an average read. In this, Paige has escaped the prison camp o**spoiler alert** I gave The Mime Order three stars because, like the other book, it was an average read. In this, Paige has escaped the prison camp of Sheol I but has become one of the most wanted criminals.What I likedI liked the story of her escaping and trying to settle in and make plans for the future, that was probably as far as I liked it.The development of Paige was incredible. I loved the way she started to be an individual by the end of the book and not scared of leaving Jaxon.Warden, oh Warden. I honestly read this book because of him and I loved every scene he was in.What I didn't likeWayyyy too much information, not much action. I went into this book hoping to see some kickass and fighting, I did not get that until the very end and was very disappointed. There was very little action and I felt as though it was just baby steps.I wish there were more scenes with the Warden because at times I just really wished we also got to see his perspective.The endingWas everything, even though it was shortlived. The kickass fighting, the jumping into others dreamscapes, taking down Jaxon and the scene where everyone found about Warden's kind. I lived for those. I kind of predicted Jaxon would go to the other side so that wasn't surprising bit nonetheless I really liked it....more

Title: the girl who smiled beads
Author: clemantine wamariya
review: “I did not understand the point of the word genocide . . . The word is tidy and efficient. It holds no true emotion. It is impersonal when it needs to“I did not understand the point of the word genocide . . . The word is tidy and efficient. It holds no true emotion. It is impersonal when it needs to be intimate, cold and sterile when it needs to be gruesome. The word is hollow, true but disingenuous, a performance, the worst kind of lie” (Wamariya 93).We know the word. We have heard the stories. Maybe we have even visited memorials, but Wamariya’s story reveals the real wound beneath the bandaid, the unvarnished reality of a child’s life torn apart by heinous atrocities. To borrow a word from Glennon Melton, this book is brutiul—full of the beauty and brutality of a life most of us can only imagine. Must read. Must witness. Must acknowledge. Must know....more

Author: taylor jenkins reid
review: 3.5Detrás de los vestidos verde esmeralda y los flashes de las alfombras rojas, Evelyn revela una vida hecha de decisiones ásperas, de amores imposibl3.5Detrás de los vestidos verde esmeralda y los flashes de las alfombras rojas, Evelyn revela una vida hecha de decisiones ásperas, de amores imposibles y de renuncias que pesan más que los premios. No busca que la juzguen, solo que la escuchen. Y al hacerlo, muestra la fragilidad de un mundo que exige perfección mientras castiga la autenticidad.Su voz fuerte, contradictoria y humana me ha hecho pensar en cuántas veces elegimos lo que se espera de nosotros y no lo que realmente somos. En lo difícil que es sostener la verdad propia en un sistema que premia las máscaras.Con una sensibilidad nada forzada, el libro también nos habla del derecho a amar sin miedo, de cuerpos que envejecen sin permiso, y de la ambición como motor, no como pecado. Evelyn no pide perdón por sobrevivir. Y eso, a su manera, también es un acto de amor.También es un recordatorio de que lo bueno y lo malo no existen como absolutos. La vida real se juega en la escala de los grises, donde cada decisión se toma desde la urgencia, el miedo, el deseo o el dolor. Evelyn no es ni ángel ni villana, es simplemente humana, y por eso su historia deja huella....more

review: A murder mystery. Art and its deeper meaning. The joy of life was replaced by silence. The talented artist never said a word again. Did she really kilA murder mystery. Art and its deeper meaning. The joy of life was replaced by silence. The talented artist never said a word again. Did she really kill her husband and why? And will psychotherapist Theo Faber be able to solve this mystery and find the reason for her silence? A tense story filled with intricate secrets. Short and vivid chapters full of little clues to be uncovered. The main character Alicia is an artist, so she very accurately conveys her feelings through her paintings. This is the book to give your parents to convince them that drugs aren't that bad... mmkay?His anecdotes seem hollow, he probably needs to eat more mushrooms (or LSD), but he had enough connections with people in the know to present the information accurately and effectively.Mostly free of religious taint. He sort of tries to explain how psychedelics work and presents some newer theories. Trying to explain how psychedelics work is as difficult as explaining consioucous and discussing the topic should be avoid unless you've spent considerable effort to understand what you're trying to explain. Title: the slow regard of silent things
Author: patrick rothfuss
review: This book was weird. I don't think I've ever read anything quite like it before. I know exactly why it was different, and am not sure how I feel aboutThis book was weird. I don't think I've ever read anything quite like it before. I know exactly why it was different, and am not sure how I feel about that: the book had no plot. I don't mean it had a bad plot, or that the plot was boring or poorly developed. I mean there was literally no plot in the book. The Slow Regard of Silent Things has no plot. It's just seven days in the life of Auri, in which nothing particularly interesting happens. Most people would think this is a bad thing for a book, and generally, I would agree with them. This book was still alright though. Not too flashy, nothing jumps out at you; it's not one of those books you can't put down. But it holds its own. You're invested in Auri's story, and you feel for her.I will say that this book is definitely NOT a good book to start on if you are interested in the Kingkiller Chronicles. You need to already know Auri before you read this book. Otherwise, it's just 177 pages about a girl with severe OCD....more

review: I'm coming to the end of Discworld. It's very sad because I've always known what book I had to read next since I started this series, and now I don'tI'm coming to the end of Discworld. It's very sad because I've always known what book I had to read next since I started this series, and now I don't have a go-to series anymore when I want to read something new. I love the way Pratchett writes. The fast-paced plots, the quirky, loveable characters, and the general absurdity of life on the Disc. I have yet to read anyone who can write better characters than Pratchett. Commander Vimes, Granny Weatherwax, and Moist Von Lipwig are my favorite characters not just of Discworld, but pretty much ever, and they all come from this series. If you haven't given Discworld a shot yet, I strongly recommend picking up a novel and seeing where it takes you....more

Title: the emperor's soul
Author: brandon sanderson
review: I got this book around lunchtime today. I finished it in an hour and a half. I loved every second of it.As always, Brandon Sanderson is brilliant. AltI got this book around lunchtime today. I finished it in an hour and a half. I loved every second of it.As always, Brandon Sanderson is brilliant. Although we are confined with Shai in her quarters for the majority of the novel, Sanderson is still able to paint us a brilliant picture of how the world works. I absolutely loved the magic system in this novel too; for some reason the idea of being able to rewrite the history of an object really appeals to me.I must admit, I was vaguely concerned that this book would not feel whole and finished, especially after reading Legion and feeling as if I only got half a story. This was not a problem for me with The Emperor's Soul. The story was whole; I didn't feel like I was missing anything. Sanderson left us at a good stopping point. And by the way, I loved the poetic symmetry of the ending. It was perfect.There was not a thing about this book I did't like. Sanderson, you have wowed me again.(view spoiler)[ Also, I am really interested to see the ramifications of Forgery in the Cosmere as a whole...I feel like this could have some very interesting effects, especially if you can Forge hemalurgic spikes so you wouldn't have to kill people anymore...or maybe the God-Metals...many possibilities here. Not entirely sure how it would work with any of the other magic systems in the Cosmere; i.e. I don't see it interacting easily with Breath or Aons, and we don't reallyknowthat much about Soulcasting yet...but anyway, that's something interesting to think about if you've read Sanderson's other Cosmere books. And if you haven't, then you probably have no idea what I'm talking about. Sorry about that. If you go read the rest of the Cosmere books and come back (and maybe also check out 17thshard.com), I promise this paragraph will make more sense.(hide spoiler)]...more

Title: words of radiance
Author: brandon sanderson
review: Words of Radiance is incredible. It’s one of those rare books that makes me wish I could give it more than five stars. Because Brandon Sanderson is aWords of Radiance is incredible. It’s one of those rare books that makes me wish I could give it more than five stars. Because Brandon Sanderson is a sneaky genius. And I can’t say anything else general without spoilers about this book because so many of the sneaky things Brandon did were at the end of the book. So don’t read the hidden part of this review unless you want massive, book-destroying spoilers. Also, most of it probably won't make sense to you if you aren't familiar with this series either, so if you haven't read Way of Kings yet, go read that and then go read Words of Radiance, andthencome back and read this review.(view spoiler)[Sanderson finally made me care about Shallan. As much as I liked Way of Kings, I felt more like I was just enduring Shallan’s chapters in order to get to the real heart of the plot. They were interesting, but the rest of the story was so much more interesting. I entered into this book expecting more of the same despite some things I’d heard from beta readers and the lucky bums who got ARCs. But then Jasnah dies (ha, nope), and the titanic weight of Jasnah’s project is thrust upon her. And she handles it. Exceptionally. I loved it. I think my favorite Shallan scene in the book was at the beginning when she saves the two caravans from bandits. That was pretty awesome.Also, I totally called the whole Jasnah still being alive thing early on. But then I kind of un-called it because of certain other protagonists Sanderson has killed off early in certain trilogies. So I guess I get partial credit for that? I was still really happy to see her in the epilogue with Wit.Also also, NIGHTBLOOD!!!!!! I was probably a little more excited to see him in here than I should have been, but ever since I became Cosmere-aware, I’ve been waiting for a noticeable main-character crossover. And before you argue, Hoid, Demoux and Galladon don’t count.I loved so much of this book and could go on for hours about my favorite parts, but there is limited space here, and I don't want to go on forever anyway, so I'll just give you three of my favorite parts of the book.1. Kaladin and Shallan getting some quality time in the Chasms. And also killing a Chasmfiend.2. Every one of Adolin's duels. Seriously. Dude is awesome.3. The final Kaladin/Szeth confrontation. If I had to choose an absolute favorite scene in WoR, this would be it. We finally get some answers about Shardblades and also get to see Kaladin fully unveil his awesomeness. And poor Szeth.(hide spoiler)]So basically, this book was awesome, and I will be absolutely shocked if it does not end up becoming my favorite book of the year. Even with Skin Game coming out in May. I plan on doing an immediate re-read at a much slower pace, but I only expect that to enhance my opinion of Words of Radiance. Truly an amazing piece of work. Congratulations, Mr. Sanderson. You have done it again....more

Title: talking to strangers
Author: malcolm gladwell
review: I was going to give this book 4 stars until I read the final chapter when I decided Malcolm had made a very persuasive argument. The whole book is a pI was going to give this book 4 stars until I read the final chapter when I decided Malcolm had made a very persuasive argument. The whole book is a persuasive argument made about situations where people generally have their minds made up about how they feel. Malcolm tries to say “let’s look closely at this for a moment” for situations where we have the privilege of retrospect. Someone does something bad and it looks bad but Malcolm says let’s look at the break down of this bad thing and let’s question the role of human judgement in that bad thing. This is not a simple argument to make. I felt myself fight back with this book a little. I think, at the end of the day, Malcolm did for me what he intended to do. He made me change my mind or at the very least, he caused me to want to think more deeply about my position....more

Title: my grandmother asked me to tell you she's sorry
Author: fredrik backman
review: "All seven-year-olds deserve superheroes and anyone who disagrees needs their head examined."This book started and ended with the same line. Reading i"All seven-year-olds deserve superheroes and anyone who disagrees needs their head examined."This book started and ended with the same line. Reading it, in the beginning, meant not very much to me as things mean little when you start a book. Reading it at the end caused me to chuckle the type of chuckle that becomes a small cry. It's the thing they say about what exists between the covers of a book, an entire story. I mean it is pretty obvious that a book will hold a story in it. What is never obvious and that you never expect is how important that story will become to you, how much emotions it will make you feel and how attached you will become to the characters in it - the characters of a story. So when at the end I felt a sadness, it was a recognizable one. It wasn't because of any heartbreaking event in the book (and this is not to say there weren't any heartbreaking events), it was because seeing those words "All seven-year-olds deserve superheroes and anyone who disagrees needs their head examined" meant I had come to the end. This sadness I felt is the sadness of having to say goodbye because while I knew they weren't real like the way people in stories aren't real, I also in a way knew that they were....more

Title: october mourning
Author: lesléa newman
review: I picked this up thinking it was going to be an LGBTQ poetry book and did not realize it was on the subject of a gay-bashing murder. However, once reaI picked this up thinking it was going to be an LGBTQ poetry book and did not realize it was on the subject of a gay-bashing murder. However, once reading it, I openly cried and felt heartbroken. The scary thing is this happened in the 80s'.... but could still happen today. So many lines in this poetry book broke my soul, especiallyI'm sorryto denyyour requestto usethe gay panic defenseForgive mefor pointing outthe obvious:there was someone gayand panicked that nightbut that someone wasn't you.Matthew Shepard was beaten, robbed, tied to a fence.. murdered. Laying tied to a fence for hours, dying in agony after five days. Just because he was gay. The story was so real .. because It was. We always think these things do not happen, people like this do not exist. My heart broke in a million pieces reading it, thinking of how many men and women today, still, are afraid of violence because of their sexuality. Title: julián is a mermaid
Author: jessica love
review: JULIAN IS A MERMAID revolves around the story of a young boy who lives with his Abuelita (grandmother) and his fascination with mermaids. All around hJULIAN IS A MERMAID revolves around the story of a young boy who lives with his Abuelita (grandmother) and his fascination with mermaids. All around him, Julian sees mermaids: or women dressed as mermaids. Julian also sees himself as a mermaid and transforms by wrapping a curtain around himself to form a 'tail'. However, his grandmother catches him- accepting him. She, in turn, takes Julian to a festival where many others are dressed as mermaids, (which upon later research is identified as the Coney Island Mermaid Parade). This LGBTQ friendly children's book breaks gender defined stereotypes and preaches words of acceptance and identity. Illustrations feature-heavy watercolor, rich color choices and detailed facial expressions. JULIAN IS A MERMAID allows us to revel in the acceptance Julian feels, while showing others how to be an ally....more

Title: the good girl
Author: mary kubica
review: **spoiler alert** Wow, what a crazy book and elements that were so unexpected. When the book first started, I wasn’t sure if it was going to captivate**spoiler alert** Wow, what a crazy book and elements that were so unexpected. When the book first started, I wasn’t sure if it was going to captivate me like I was hoping, but as the story progressed I couldn’t seem to stop reading it. The authors use of perspective and time manipulation really gives the book its mysterious nature. You get to see the almost obsession this detective has with finding Mia, the girl who’s been kidnapped, and you get to find out how much her mom wishes she would have stood up for Mia more. The most interesting perspective though would be the kidnapper, Colin. Throughout the story you can see that his thinking changes and his point of view takes a turn. Mia’s perspective is nonexistent through the book up until the last chapter, and you see that it’s because she knows more than she lets on. The author use of perspective was so smart because of reveals so much and gives a last unexpected twist. The time aspect is what keeps this book rolling, because everything is out of order snd switches off to before and after Mia is found, and then by the end of the book it seems as though it meets in the middle and everything makes more sense. I would recommend this book to mostly young adult readers or people go enjoy mystery novels. I really enjoyed this book and I appreciate the effort that you can see in the authors writing....more

Title: sea of strangers
Author: lang leav
review: A central idea that I think could be seen, is the pattern of heartbreak and loss to resiliency. It is clear that a lot of this book is about the painA central idea that I think could be seen, is the pattern of heartbreak and loss to resiliency. It is clear that a lot of this book is about the pain that she feels when during these hard times. It’s one of the hardest things to notice that a relationship is starting to diminish, and there is nothing that you can do about it. You can see her struggle with this in the book and see that she longs for the way that things used to be. But then at certain points in the book just when you think that this is her breaking point, she rises back up to the top to claim her life as her own. She realizes that she doesn't need the love she thought to be happy. It’s a clear cycle of this.The way that Lang Leav uses her words is a very beautiful thing. In the book she often uses metaphors or similes to show her symbolism. In one of her poems “From a Dream” she states the way it felt to love this certain person by comparing it to waking up from a dream, and the few seconds after it. It really helps to put things in perspective. Something that really influences her imagery is her personification. Many times she likes to talk about people like being the sun and the moon. One place you can see this is in her poem “Reclaiming the sky”, where she sends a powerful message about rising up and claiming what is rightfully yours.This is a really great book. I’m usually not the type of person that sits down with a book full of poems, but this surprised me. It’s such a trip to see these stories go on such a ride of emotions. You see heartbreak and loneliness, all the way to being on top and you don’t need anyone to make you whole. It’s almost empowering to see that no matter how low things get, things can still look up and change. I can tell from this book that Lang Leav has an amazing way with how she uses her words. She takes time to perfect and execute her ideas....more

Title: since you've been gone

review: Since You’ve Been Gone, starts out by talking about one of the main focuses of the book, Sloane. Sloane has recently gone missing along with her familSince You’ve Been Gone, starts out by talking about one of the main focuses of the book, Sloane. Sloane has recently gone missing along with her family, only leaving behind a to-do list for the main character Emily. The only way that emily can think of to bring her best friend back is to do the list of things that are normally way out of her comfort zone. So, she starts with the small things. Through this journey, Emily never expects the full ride of emotions and new opportunities that she is going to find, along with discovering herself.I believe that the main romance of this book is very believable. You can see that at the beginning of this book Emily is very introspective. She has a hard time connecting to people and getting out of her shell to finish the list, which is why I think it’s good that Morgan Matson didn’t go too fast with the relationship. She gives a good amount of time so that Emily has a chance to get to know herself a little first, before throwing her into a relationship. It makes this book a lot more meaningful, because it’s not so far out that you can’t relate to it.I really love this book. I think that Morgan Matson does a great job of showing character development through Emily. One thing that I think is subtle but makes the book more personal to the author is the song mix’s that Frank and Emily make for each other. It is a great way to incorporate some of the things that the author loves while also making it valuable to the story. Morgan Matson paints a picture with her quality of writing, and her ability to story tell....more

Title: the girl on the train
Author: paula hawkins
review: The Girl on the Train is about a woman named Emma Watson, who is unusually observant about the world around her. Mostly, she focuses on the houses thaThe Girl on the Train is about a woman named Emma Watson, who is unusually observant about the world around her. Mostly, she focuses on the houses that she passes on her daily train ride and the people that live in them. Since she has not actually met these people she takes note on what they do everyday, and makes up her own version of what their life is like. She takes particular interest in one family that she believes has a perfect life. When the girl, she calls Jess, doesn’t show up for a couple days, she starts to worry just enough to investigate.The author, Paula Hawkins, loves to throw flashbacks in there when she knows that, without it, the book wouldn’t make sense. This adds a lot of suspense because until you get the whole story, you can’t make a prediction about the ending. She goes into such death that the book goes on pretty long before you can really get the plot of the book. Paula Hawkins does an amazing job with manipulating the time. The ending has a big surprise and can get confusing if the person reading does not pay enough attention.I really enjoyed this book but at a couple of points it got a little long. Before all of the action has started the author takes a long time to get to the point. Of course, that can be caused by the fact that a lot of background information is needed to understand why Emma is the way she is and really get the depth. The reader has to pay a lot of attention to the detail or else you will get lost in the story. Paula Watson has a very interesting type of writing, which makes it very interesting and is also why I liked this book....more

Title: miss peregrine's home for peculiar children

review: The main character of the book that I am reading is named Jacob. He is an ordinary boy until his grandpa dies and jacob is convinced that he saw the mThe main character of the book that I am reading is named Jacob. He is an ordinary boy until his grandpa dies and jacob is convinced that he saw the monster that killed his grandfather. He is also convinced that it was a monster that killed his grandpa. Nobody else believes him. Then he meets some very strange people and becomes friends with them. These kids are strange not only in their personality, but also in their physical traits as well.The author of the book that I am reading creates mystery and suspense by multiple of the main things that create suspense. One of the big things that the author uses is pacing. She uses pacing in multiple ways. She uses it in the whole book. And she also uses it in the way that she tells the little stories within the main book. Another one that she uses is telling the story out of order. She jumps a lot and you are always wondering what happened next and/or what happened to the person or character that she switched from. The author also uses a lot of the gothic characteristics. One of the ones that she uses is with the characters. The monsters in the book have red eyes and are often hidden except for the telltale signs. She also does unexpected twists in the story. I have gotten really excited about something in the book because I think that I know what is going to happen, but then she throws something completely different than I was expecting.My opinion of the book that I am reading is a good book. It does swear a lot and a lot of people didn‚Äôt finish reading it because of the language. It is a great book besides the language. The characters are honest and solve their problems. Title: we come apart
Author: sarah crossan
review: In this book Nicu and Jess both get caught stealing and have to go to a ‘reparation’ camp for troubled youth. Nicu comes from Romania and does not speIn this book Nicu and Jess both get caught stealing and have to go to a ‘reparation’ camp for troubled youth. Nicu comes from Romania and does not speak english very well but is trying hard to fit in despite being bullied constantly for his race. Jess has an abusive step father at home who beats her mother. The two meet through the camp and begin talking and hanging out. Jess finds herself being able to confide in Nicu. Nicu finds a friend amidst all the attacks from his school mates. Together they help each other overcome their individual roadblocks.I had never read a novel in verse before and was wary about the fact that the authors have to write a story in short simple poems. I didn’t think that was possible, but it was! Sarah Crossan and Brian Conaghan tell a beautiful story through beautiful poems. It had a romantic, whimsical feel that came from the poems. There was imagery, sensory detail, metaphors, similes, euphony, and foreshadowing. Each poetic device added to the story and made it interesting. The poetic devices helped develop the theme by brightening each of the character’s voices. When there was a specific moment the authors wanted captured, they were able to do so with poetic devices.I really loved this book! It was amazing for my first novel in verse that I read and I love how different the style is from actual novels. The authors were able to bring the characters to life and there was never an empty moment. The plot was interesting but had a few twists and turns I felt were unbelievable and contradictory to the characters/story. The ending was sad but sweet and I enjoyed every second of this book, I ended up reading it in a day because it captured my attention. I recommend this book to anyone who is looking for a new style of writing to read, likes reading about healing relationships or wants a quickread with a little heartbreak....more

Title: geekerella

review: In this fractured fairy tale version of Cinderella, Elle Wittimer is a orphan stuck with the meanest step-mother known to man. Darien Freeman is sickIn this fractured fairy tale version of Cinderella, Elle Wittimer is a orphan stuck with the meanest step-mother known to man. Darien Freeman is sick of never being in control of anything. When the two meet randomly through a wrong number situation, they begin to talk and get to know each other. The catch is that Darien Freeman is famous and filming the movie remake of Elle’s favorite show, Starfield. The clashing of their two worlds is well written and the love story is super cute.This book tackled a lot of stigmas very well which is why a lot of people rated this book very high. I have to agree, the author, Ashley Poston, worked hard to correct some of the stereotypes of geeks and nerds and it worked very well with the story line. This book is rated a lot higher than I thought it would be. Most of the reviews don’t talk about how the meeting between the main characters wasn’t done the best and I think it could have been done better. The ending wasn’t satisfying in my opinion. I do agree that this was a super fun, warm, heartfelt read, like most of the reviews say.This book was so cute! The main characters had a perfect romance that made my heart melt. I only gave this book three stars though because I feel like it missed the mark on a few points. First I think that some of the subplots needed to be fleshed out more or completely removed. They didn’t add anything to the story and left me confused. Also, this book was very superficial feeling for me even though it tackled some ‘deep’ topics. I think that Poston could have added more emotional depth to the characters. Overall, if you are looking for a cute, sweet, quick read, this book is for you....more

Title: carry on
Author: rainbow rowell
review: Simon Snow is a magical anomaly. They call him the Chosen One, but he couldn't feel further from that. He causes disruptions wherever he goes and wantSimon Snow is a magical anomaly. They call him the Chosen One, but he couldn't feel further from that. He causes disruptions wherever he goes and wants to finish his final year of school in peace. That doesn't happen when his roommate, Baz, comes back to school two months late looking like a complete wreck. While Baz was gone, Simon got a message from Baz's mom. They may hate each other, but they are forced to work together (and maybe realize their feelings for each other).This relationship was amazing! Simon and Baz are obviously meant for each other, even though they pretend to hate each other. While the relationship is set in a fantasy universe, I find the relationship believable. There were a few moments when I thought that they would never get over their misplaced hatred for one another, but as they talked and really got to see each other in a new light, they fell head over heels for each other. Overall, I thought it was a beautiful, believable, and for the most part, realistic relationship.I loved this book! As I mentioned above, the relationship that unfolded throughout the book was soft with the perfect amount of angst. The plot was enthralling with great character development, well-written alternate POVs and enough surprise to keep me guessing. Rainbow Rowell has prose that I really enjoy reading and her passion for writing is evident in this book. I can't wait for the second book!...more

Title: delirium
Author: lauren oliver
review: Delirium is a dystopian book about a society where love is considered a disease. It is told from the perspective of Lena, who is living with her auntDelirium is a dystopian book about a society where love is considered a disease. It is told from the perspective of Lena, who is living with her aunt and has been since her mom committed suicide. Her best friend Hana trespasses into a laboratory and convinces Lena to go with her. Together they meet a guy their age, Alex. Lena and Alex have some obvious chemistry, Alex attracted to Lena, and Lena not sure if she trusts him. This starts Lena’s realization that the government may be corrupt in making love against the law.Lena is very complex and changes in major ways throughout the book. She starts by being a strict law abiding citizen and believing everything the government told her. Through her dreams about her mom’s suicide and Hana, she starts to explore the flaws of this society, and the benefits of not following the laws. It is a gradual then almost immediate change. Lena starts slowly breaking laws, and then all of a sudden does not believe in them at all when she falls in love with Alex.Delirium is a book that I really enjoyed reading. The characters had good development and the plot continually surprised me. There were a few lulls were it took me some time to get back into the story, but overall the book kept me intrigued. The author, Lauren Oliver was very good in showing the meaning behind simple phrases. Because of this though, she used a lot of similes. Almost every paragraph could be found with a simile of some kind starting with the phrase ‘as if’ or ‘it was as though’ etc. Once I realized this, it was hard to not notice every single one and that made reading slightly more distracting for me. Overall, this book was very interesting and was written in a way that I had not yet experienced, but I hated the ending. Absolutely thought it was awful. I will not be reading the next two books in the series, I cannot be bothered....more

Title: hidden figures
Author: margot lee shetterly
review: 1. My central idea of the book is ‘hard work pays off’ and in this situation it did. In Hidden Figures three African American women proved their smart1. My central idea of the book is ‘hard work pays off’ and in this situation it did. In Hidden Figures three African American women proved their smarts and worked hard to be able to work on the Nasa space team, in which later they got to watch the rocket fly into space. In these times the white race was not nice to the darker race, in ways that were utterly unnecessary. If these women had not worked hard they would not have gotten where they were, their hard work had paid off.2. I think the the word that stuck out the most was “underestimate”. I say this word because the whole story behind this book was four African American women getting the chance to work with Nasa on the space launch, and this was set in the time where the whites were said to be the best race. The darker skinned people were treated poorly and often times called names such as dumb. But these women proved to those around them that they could be just as smart, or smarter than they are. The words definition in the dictionary is “estimate (something) to be smaller or less important than it actually is” which is slightly different than the meaning that was given in the book. In the book they use it as not being capable of doing something so they thought down on them.3. I loved this book because of how strong the novel showed emotion. While reading the book it left you connecting to all the characters in your own way, as well as sometimes getting frustrated with certain people in the book. It was fun to read because it also taught you a little history lesson about how the African Americans had been treated. Hidden Figures gives you a perspective that you wouldn’t expect to see....more

Title: divergent
Author: veronica roth
review: There are five factions, The Dauntless, Amity, Abnegation, Candor, and Erudite, and each faction is based on their nature. Abnegation; the selfless, DThere are five factions, The Dauntless, Amity, Abnegation, Candor, and Erudite, and each faction is based on their nature. Abnegation; the selfless, Dauntless; the brave, Amity; the peaceful, Erudite; the intelligent, and Candor; the honest. Beatrice is currently living in the Abnegation sector, and like the temperament that describes the Abnegation, Beatrice is no different. The main character of the book, Beatrice Prior, turns sixteen and the big day comes for her to take the aptitude test and leave her family and join a new faction. The aptitude test is a test that determines one's skills and abilities. Whatever the sixteen year olds score on their test determines which fraction they can join out of the five. After Beatrice takes the test her results come back being Divergent, which leaves her not being to fit into just one fraction, but a bit of all of them. From there on out she has to hide her results to save her life.In the beginning of this book Beatrice was very selfless, just as her fraction raised her to be. She was also very shy and stayed in very close quarters of her comfort zone. As the book progressed, Beatrice was no longer Beatrice. She now went by Tris in her new fraction of the brave, the Dauntless. By the first day she was there she was already taking massive steps outside her comfort zone. Being in Dauntless meant confronting your fears and trying to overcome them, learning to fight, and get to the top of your class. Tris knew that in order to make it out alive she had to make it to the top, so she did just that. She pushed her boundaries and continued to fight. She became a stronger person and was no longer the shy little girl she had started out in the beginning.I thought this book was very impressive with how it was written and how every turn was unexpected and exciting. Most of the chapters of this book had left you on cliffhangers, which I really enjoy. They always seem to get me more indulged in the book and not want to put it down. I related to Tris Prior and most of her thoughts. When I read about her I always thought about myself thinking about the spot she was in, or had been in the past and how we were alike. There were other characters that I also thought I had a close connection with such as Christina and Four. All the characters were very different and their personalities ranged from various scales, which were really fun to read about. My favorite part of the book was in the beginning when Tris had to enter her fears and try to conquer them, it was fun to read and even got me feeling the anxiety that she had....more

Title: steelheart
Author: brandon sanderson
review: **spoiler alert** Everything starts with the Annexation, the day Steelheart turned the land to steel, the day he killed David's father. After the deat**spoiler alert** Everything starts with the Annexation, the day Steelheart turned the land to steel, the day he killed David's father. After the death David did nothing but prepare for the day he would get his revenge. He was determined to learn everything he could about epics (people who'd been gifted with powers) and their weakness, all epics had one. However he could not do it alone, so he set out to gather all the information he could on the Reckoners, the only group of people who was willing to fight against epics and their evil reign. It took time but he finally found where one of their operations would be and was able to join them. He convinced them to go after higher more powerful epics, unlike previous ones they'd killed in the past. They saw a great risk in this but also saw a great win. Killing higher epics in Steelhearts territory would draw him out and give them the opportunity to attack him. The only problem was, they didn't know his weakness. David had seen him bleed, it was the reason his father had been killed. his father had wounded Steelheart, but how had he done it? David could not figure it out until the day game where he was face to face with steel heart. Him and the Reckoners and drawn him out, pretending to be an epic that was there to challenge him. They were being defeated but David would not back down. He faced Steelheart and realized how his father had wounded Steelheart. It had not been intentionally, he'd been trying to save Steelheart from another epic because his father believed that the epics were supposed to be their to help them. However that was not the reason he had been wounded. It was because he had not feared Steelheart. After David came to this realization, he too lost fear for Steelheart, and so, he shot. Killing Steelheart.Though I did not go into a lot of detail I really loved this story because one, I love anything that incorporates special abilities or powers and this book does that. Not only that it gives these powerful beings a flaw, a way to be beaten, and just the way the characters have to figure these weaknesses out and execute plans to exploit the weakness is amazing. It's a fun book with great characters that you can relate to, whether its challenges their facing, or emotions their feeling, you really just get that shared connection. Another thing I enjoyed is that it is well paced, it doesn't start you off with that great intro and then just explain to you day by day everything David is up to. It incorporates his time since the events of his fathers death well into the story on later pages. Fitting in with the events that are taking place.I gave it a five star rating not because it's about humans with powers and gadgets, though that does play into the reason, but because it is a well crafted work that balances its self out with character developments, setting description, background information, and great twists that when re read can leave you thinking, "That makes so much sense now!", "That's why they were the way they were!". It is just a really great book all around and I can't wait to read the next one....more

Title: long way down
Author: jason reynolds
review: **spoiler alert** Long Way Down is a powerful short story written in free-verse. It follows the story of Will, a teenager who just witnessed his broth**spoiler alert** Long Way Down is a powerful short story written in free-verse. It follows the story of Will, a teenager who just witnessed his brother get murdered. The place he lives has three rules passed from father to son: don’t cry, don’t snitch, and avenge a loved one’s murder. With these rules in mind, Will wipes the tears before they can form and heads to where he thinks his brother’s murderer is, gun in his belt. However, once Will gets into the elevator six dead people from his past enter the elevator one-by-one and tell him how they met their demise. The author beautifully constructs these encounters, allowing the encounters to build up impact until the final two words of the story. It is shown that each of these people reveal a flaw in Will’s plan. It starts out with Buck, who shows Will isn’t prepared, then Dani who reveals Will’s reluctance to kill someone, then his uncle Mark, who exacerbates Will’s reluctance to kill, then his dad shows up and reveals that he followed the third rule and killed Mark’s killer, but killed the wrong person and got killed by the victim’s family. Frick is the fifth person to enter, and it is found out he is the one who killed Buck and was killed by Will’s brother, and someone from Frick’s gang killed Will’s brother to get revenge. Lastly, Will’s brother walked into the elevator but says nothing to Will. When the elevator reaches the lobby, everyone disappears except Will’s brother, who walks out of the elevator and says two words: “You coming?”. The author slowly reveals the cycle of death the third rule brings, and those last two words say everything: is Will going to kill his brother’s killer and ultimately get meet the same fate as everyone else in the elevator?....more

Title: quarter life poetry
Author: samantha jayne
review: The central idea of this book was about troubles and mishaps in your early twenties. All of the poems in this book started out as poems and drawings tThe central idea of this book was about troubles and mishaps in your early twenties. All of the poems in this book started out as poems and drawings that were posted to the author’s Instagram, and she eventually compiled them into a book. The poems cover different aspects in after college life and all of them usually have a humorous tone to them.There aren’t many poetic devices that I could spot in this book. There are a few examples of hyperbole, as is very common in comedy, specifically about life. However, the rhyme schemes are extremely clever, and are almost perfect examples of how to rhyme with a humorous effect. This amazing rhyming persists throughout the collection, and the quality of the creative rhymes never lowers or wavers.I enjoyed the book quite a bit. It brought a few chuckles to me, and I would imagine it would be relatable if I was in my post-college years. Although sometimes it seemed the book got a bit preachy, they were very small and didn’t occur very frequently. Overall, I thought it was a pretty good book and was able to make poetry seem less like something that pushovers and english nerds do, and something that can be made funny and done by everyday people....more

Title: the house of hades
Author: rick riordan
review: **spoiler alert** In the fourth book of the Heroes of Olympus series, The House of Hades, the heroes face their largest, and most impactful choice yet**spoiler alert** In the fourth book of the Heroes of Olympus series, The House of Hades, the heroes face their largest, and most impactful choice yet. Their friends Annabeth and Percy have just fallen into Tartarus, and have a slim chance of survival on their own. But they also just got the Athena Parthenos, which will diffuse the growing tensions between camp half blood and camp jupiter. They are now faced with a choice that will affect much more than themselves. Should they take the Athena Parthenos to camp half blood but let their friends face certain death, or should they go and open the Doors of Death and risk another millenium long war between the roman and greek demigods?There are four main romances in the book. There is the romance between Frank, the shapeshifting son of Mars, and Hazel, the daughter of Pluto. The second romance within the book is between Jason, the son of Jupiter, and Piper, the daughter of Aphrodite. The third, and newest romance is between Leo, the mechanic son of Hephaestus, and Calypso. The final, and most shown romance is between Percy, the son of Poseidon, and Annabeth, the daughter of Athena. I feel like all of them are believable because they all grow over time, and their personalities make sense going together. I feel like the romance enhanced my experience of the book because it got me to care about the characters and how they interacted with each other even more.I really enjoyed the book. The characters were amazing and were easy to care about, and I wanted good things to happen to them. The writing is really good, and it makes you feel what the characters are feeling with good description. For example, while Percy and Annabeth are drinking from the river that runs through Tartarus because they are desperate, and it is described as being hot yet cold at the same time, and I could feel what that would be like because of the description. Another example of this effect is when they eat for the first time since arriving in Tartarus, and it describes how stuffed they were, and how easily they drifted off to sleep, which I could understand that feeling, and it enhanced my overall enjoyment of the book....more

Title: the nightingale
Author: kristin hannah
review: It goodREREAD REVIEWWhile rereading The Nightingale, it has not moved from the pedestal I put it on. There are some points in the beginning of the booIt goodREREAD REVIEWWhile rereading The Nightingale, it has not moved from the pedestal I put it on. There are some points in the beginning of the book when I noticed the characters acted in an unusual way, but it wasn't anything major. The characters were amazing, and the story was still one of these best I've experienced in any medium. The characters undergo extreme character growth brought upon by the war, and it all makes sense. It makes sense that Isabelle would temper her attitude when the danger of imprisonment and execution are always looming around the corner. It makes sense Vianne would become much harder and colder than she was previously with Nazis staying in her house. The best thing this book accomplishes though, is the atmosphere it creates. Just like the first reading of this, I would get sucked into the world the author has masterfully created. The only other books that have sucked me in this much are the Eragon books, but this book has the advantage of a simple thing: better writing and storytelling. This book is intense, emotional, and riveting. I recommend this book to anyone regardless of their preferences. This story can be enjoyed by anyone because it has so many different genres all mixed masterfully....more

review: I do not often enjoy the second book in a trilogy, however, Prodigy was different. Very often the second book has a filler feel; meaning, it doesn’t rI do not often enjoy the second book in a trilogy, however, Prodigy was different. Very often the second book has a filler feel; meaning, it doesn’t really add to the story, it merely fills pages. Prodigy on the other hand, was interesting, it introduced important new characters and filled many of the gaps presented in Legend. The unique writing of the two main characters truly feels individual, making the characters seem realistic. Prodigy and the Legend series is really captivating. I would suggest it to anyone who enjoys dystopian love stories with a fun twist. My only problem is the way the dystopian outside world is introduced; however, the third book may clear up confusion....more

Title: allegiant
Author: veronica roth
review: When genetic scientists discovered the genes that code for undesirable traits such as cowardice and stupidity they used their advanced technology to “When genetic scientists discovered the genes that code for undesirable traits such as cowardice and stupidity they used their advanced technology to “fix” humankind and change DNA. This resulted in the purity wars, a war between the genetically pure (people without genetic changes) and the genetically damaged (individuals with altered DNA), this war devastated billions of people and greatly decreased the Earth's population. Fast forward several decades, after the purity wars, and the bureau of genetic welfare has tried to undo the alterations in human DNA. They have done this by creating enclosed areas where the damaged individuals have their genes corrected and then pass down the whole genes to their children, and create a new population of genetically pure individuals. Tris and Tobias come from one of these genetic experiments, but in this city the society has collapsed and innocent people are being killed by the government. Tris and Tobias escape Chicago with a group of friends only to find that the world outside their city is just as corrupted if not more than the place they just left. Now they must choose their morals, choose who they trust, ultimately choose the fate of every person they know and love.Tris and Tobias are very interesting characters. They experience devastating loss and mind boggling moral dilemmas as the plot thickens. With their challenges they only grow stronger and more individual. At the start of the story they find themselves struggling to sort out their opinions and moral standpoints and throughout the book become grounded in their values. Eventually they make up for past and recent differences and complications and grow to have a stronger less controlling relationship which Tris really struggled with. As they develop and the plot thickens the couple learns the importance of standing for what they believe in without making rash decisions.Allegiant and the entire divergent series were very fun to read, I loved the moral delmas that the characters faced. The plot was fascinating, as the story progressed my excitement and intrigue in the story increasted. The love story between Tris and Tobias was unbelievably annoying, their relationship was unrealistic and the continual circle of fighting was frustrating. The conclusion of the story was also predictable which made reading the whole series feel like a waste of time. All in all the novel was interesting but the love scenes were boring and the conclusion was lame....more

Title: the sword of summer
Author: rick riordan
review: The book is about a homeless kid named Magnus Chase he starts out sleeping under a bridge and then breaks into his uncle’s house there he meets hisThe book is about a homeless kid named Magnus Chase he starts out sleeping under a bridge and then breaks into his uncle’s house there he meets his uncle and then drives to a bridge. At the bridge he dies he is resurrected into the norse or viking afterlife having made it into Odin's great hall, Valhalla. He proceeds to get his Valkyrie out of Valhalla and then escapes valhalla on a quest for the sword of summer. He runs around the nine worlds of norse mythology meeting giants sea monsters and various gods. He meets famous figures in norse mythology such as Loki, Thor, Odin and Freya.Most people on Goodreads said they wanted Magnus Chase to be Annabeth's, one of Rick Riordan’s characters in the Percy Jackson series, brother. I don’t think this is true and another reviewer said this which I think made a great point to the separation, putting Magnus as Annabeths cousin allows for easier connection to Percy jackson while also keeping the series somewhat separate. Most of the reviewers on Goodreads want Percy Jackson to be in this series right away I completely disagree. It’s not bad to have a connective universe but there's a point where a connective series and constantly bringing it around like this gets annoying. Authors should be able to make their own stand alone series when an author constantly has to fall back onto an earlier series and books it makes the series weak. This isn’t shared by others my personal opinion doesn't make sense to me but I guess they like the same thing over and over again.It’s a good book and does a better job at keeping to the true norse mythology than most with a few liberties such as Geirod and his daughters who in norse mythology were killed by Thor. The character is relatable and has a great personality. On of my biggest problems with this series and Rick Riordan's books in general is the insistence on crossovers and the main character having an algorithm the character starts out good but by the end of the first and beginning of the second is basically just another Percy Jackson. By the end of this book his character loses what made him so good in the first place and it seriously reduces the books quality. Overall good book and awesome subject but needs work on the character....more

Title: i am malala
Author: malala yousafzai
review: The book "I am Malala" is written by Malala Yousafzai. This books talks about her fight for women's right to an education in Pakistan. Her father wasThe book "I am Malala" is written by Malala Yousafzai. This books talks about her fight for women's right to an education in Pakistan. Her father was a professor at one of the schools in their country and he encouraged her to go to school to learn. One day on her way home from school she was shot in the head by a Taliban gunman, as did her friends that were with her on her bus. After she was able to recover she went into public speaking in order to get rights for women in her country. I love how she's not afraid to fight for what she believes in, no matter the danger that she could be in. She does the right thing to do for the benefit of others, which I think is amazing. I would recommend this book to anyone and everyone because I think its something that people need to hear, weither they are male or female, Pakistan or American; it's important to know how actions effect people and that you need to see other peoples point of view. Title: the fault in our stars
Author: john green
review: The fault in our stars is about a Hazel Grace fighting through cancer while falling in love. Her mom suggests that she joins a support group so she caThe fault in our stars is about a Hazel Grace fighting through cancer while falling in love. Her mom suggests that she joins a support group so she can talk to other kids also battling cancer. After going she makes friends Augustus who is there supporting his friend. Augustus invites Hazel to a movie and from there on out their relationship only grows. Hazel tells Augustus about this book that she loves An Imperial Affliction. Augustus finds away for her to ask the other in the book a bunch of questions about the book, the author lives in Amsterdam so the two and Hazel's mom take a trip. To find out the rest you should read the book.I think that is book is pretty believable. You can relate to the characters and you can understand where they are coming from. Obviously you can’t understand everything because not everyone has cancer, but you can see where they are coming from. Now somethings aren’t very realistic, but it’s a romance novel so what else can you expect? No one has that perfect relationship. This however, doesn’t affect my opinion of the book at all. I thought it was a good book. All romance books have unrealistic relationships so I was expecting it as I went into the book.I loved this book. It wasn’t just a love story though it was a story about loss and hardships. I think that is one of the reasons why the book is so loved and well known. It’s relate-able even if you can’t relate completely you still feel a connection between you and the characters in the book.Reread ReviewThe book is still equally as amazing as the first time that I read it. This being my second time reading it, I was able to catch things that hinted to the ending of the book. There was also a lot of other metaphors that I didn't under stand too much of the first time that I was reading the book. John Green is an amazing writer. Rereading of "The Fault in Our Stars" made it able for me to look at all the things that I didn't catch the first time. The book is amazing really one of the best books that I've ever read. I could read it many more times and it still wouldn't get old. I'm sure with each time that I would read it, there would be something new for me to find....more

Title: becoming
Author: michelle obama
review: Becoming by Michelle Obama is mostly about Michelle’s life. It talked about the events that happened that made Michelle, Michelle. In the book it talkBecoming by Michelle Obama is mostly about Michelle’s life. It talked about the events that happened that made Michelle, Michelle. In the book it talks a lot about the struggle of being black and talking like a white person in a black community. Michelle had to fix the way that she acted and talked around certain people. Michelle goes talks the reader through her life starting at the begin when she was a kid living in the south of Chicago to her being one of america's most famous first ladies.An idea that was repeated in the book a lot was “be who you are.” Michelle faced a lot of obstacles that challenged who she was. At times it almost got to her but she never let those obstacles change her identity. The dictionary has two very different definitions for the word identity. One is “the fact of being who or what a person or thing is.” This is the definition that Michelle is trying to get across. The second one is, “a close similarity or affinity” this definition is the exact opposite of what is implied in Becoming. In the book she talks about not being the same and being her own person. What I find as interesting is that one word could have two completely different meanings.I honestly loved this book. I learned some things from it about Michelle and some things about life. When I was reading this book I could Michelle's voice. The way as speaking in the text sounded like the same way that Michelle would talk in a normal conversation. I loved learning about her life. You normally just see that outside of a person but when you get to learn more and go deeper into that person's life you are able to know and understand that person a little more....more

Title: the girl with seven names

review: “The Girl with Seven Names” by Hyeonseo Lee is a story about a young girl that defects from North Korea. It was an eye opener for me because although“The Girl with Seven Names” by Hyeonseo Lee is a story about a young girl that defects from North Korea. It was an eye opener for me because although I knew that North Korea was ruthless and oppressive, I didn’t know the extent of their cruel laws and policies. Hyeonseo grew up in a village on the border between the North and China. And a month before she turned 18, she illegally crossed the border to visit some family friends in China. But things didn’t go as planned and she couldn’t return, so she worked and was able to get asylum in South Korea. She then helped her mom and brother get to South Korea. I really enjoyed the story and would strongly recommend it to people that want to learn more about the world we live in and how blessed we are to live here in America....more

Title: quarter life poetry
Author: samantha jayne
review: All youth, who think you are extraordinary (or weird), it’s okay. Actually, we all think we are the center of the earth. Oh yeah! Struggle is real. IAll youth, who think you are extraordinary (or weird), it’s okay. Actually, we all think we are the center of the earth. Oh yeah! Struggle is real. I think we might have been born to struggle. But, what makes me feel better is that at least this book is talking about a “Quarter” of our life which is 25/100=¼ which is our youth, our burning days: all the obstacles, all the small worries and happiness. It’s all about the thing we have already been through, currently in middle of the situation, or we will be going to go through. This book applies to me; I feel like I can project myself in this book. This book makes me feel like even though I struggle, it’s okay, because that is just part of youth.Poems in this book makes me feel like one topic and short story. This book is hyper realistic. Poems in this book literally reflect ourselves.This book use a lot of rhyming and sarcasm jokes. All poem in this book brings a lot of imagery. Because this book use a lot of creative draws that help us we can connect the poem and our experience. But this book also use symbolism too. Because it criticize our lifestyle too. In the poem in the chapter Money,In the poem in the chapter Money,I don’t need to exercise‘cause i already sweatWhen i contemplate the deptOf my student loan debt.Especially this kind of poem bring our age’s sympathy. This is the things make this book creative.I hate school English class when they makes me to analyze what is the thing, imply in tiny tiny verse. Which is no sympathy to me. I thought this is why people hate to read poems. When you being super strict picky reader and trying to conquer the poem. It reduce actual fun of read poems. But this book is literally can be me. I finish this book really fast and i really enjoyed it. Even i read author's Instagram sun-dance interviews video and short clip video about poems in this book. This book really soak in inside of the poem. It did really good job to express our ‘Quarter’ zone people's real life and our emotion. I recommend for all of us so those who want to struggle better....more
