Title: the wright brothers
Author: david mccullough
review: This book was probably one of the most interesting books about any important historical figures I've ever read. Most biographies and memoirs are slighThis book was probably one of the most interesting books about any important historical figures I've ever read. Most biographies and memoirs are slightly interesting in some aspects, but I've noticed that a lot of them give a lot of small unimportant detail that is often unnecessary but this one wasn't as bad because all the details were somehow related to how they affected the brothers and influenced them to invent flight. The Wright brothers were an inspiring couple, they came from a family where they were loved and treated kindly by their parents. Their father was a bishop and helped them develop into who they became in their adult lives. The brothers were good friends, and you can see this from the very beginning of the book when they describe their arguments as something awful. I would recommend this to anyone just because it is such an inspirational book. I think it would help people recognize their opportunities and try to be creative like the wright brothers were. It would teach people that they can do things that have never been done before. It was a little bit of a challenge to read, but I think most other high schoolers could read it....more

Title: the invention of wings

The first time I read "Everything Everything," I paid more attention to the storyline ratheI think that it was very interesting to reread this book. The first time I read "Everything Everything," I paid more attention to the storyline rather than noticing small details. Title: eleanor & park
Author: rainbow rowell
review: I gave this book four stars, because since reading it, it has become one of my favorite books. I think that the author really expressed the story ofI gave this book four stars, because since reading it, it has become one of my favorite books. I think that the author really expressed the story of a young romance perfectly. Although the characters went through stages of awkwardness, anxiety, and desperation, they also went through stages of happiness, truth, and pure love. The story showed a relationship that was imperfectly perfect. Eleanor and Park had their rough patches, but they were able to work through them together, because they learned what it truly means to love someone. The author made her characters flawed and relatable. I was able to connect with both characters through one way or another. I like that the story was so raw and realistic in that way. Overall, I think this book is definitely worth reading and I recommend it to anyone else that loves a good romance....more

Title: the fault in our stars
Author: john green
review: In the book, Hazel Grace-a lung cancer patient-meets a boy named Augustus (Gus) Waters-who has osteosarcoma-at her support group. Together, they helpIn the book, Hazel Grace-a lung cancer patient-meets a boy named Augustus (Gus) Waters-who has osteosarcoma-at her support group. Together, they help their mutual friend Isaac through losing his vision due to eye cancer. They fall in love and experience not only their own trials of cancer, but each other's. Gus takes Hazel to Amsterdam to meet her idol, Peter Van Houten. When they get back from Amsterdam, Gus tells Hazel that his condition is getting worse.Some reviewers thought that it was good that Hazel and Gus were in love. I agree, but I think that this idea is debatable. It might have been bad that they were together, because they had to worry about each others' health conditions rather than just their own. It was sad for them when things got worse and sometimes Hazel would wonder whether or not she was willing to let Augustus into her life. However, I think that it was good that they were together, because they were able to relate to each other. They made the best out of what they had.I loved reading this book so much. I think that it was written beautifully. The author understood the hardships of cancer and he was able to describe it so well. I loved the story and it was fun to feel so involved in Gus and Hazel's relationship. It helped me to develop more compassion and sympathy for cancer victims. The book was entertaining, sad, hilarious, and sweet all at the same time. Overall, this book is amazing and I think that everyone should read it....more

Title: the selection
Author: kiera cass
review: America Singer is faced with the choice of entering a competition to become the queen or remaining with her true love. She chooses to participate in tAmerica Singer is faced with the choice of entering a competition to become the queen or remaining with her true love. She chooses to participate in the competition because of the benefits it will bring her family. She discovers that the competition isn't all that bad. However, her boyfriend decides to get a job at the castle where their secret love affair continues. She struggles to choose whether she should be with her boyfriend or the prince.I think that the romance in this book is very believable. It shows the reality of relationships. Sometimes people lie in relationships because they think that it will be better for the other person. However, lying to someone is rarely ever the answer. The story also explains how sometimes it is hard to date and choose somebody over another person.I really enjoyed the book because there were many interesting plot twists. I never knew exactly what to expect and I could not tell who she was going to be with in the end. The story line was interesting and I liked the futuristic dystopia concept. Although the book was slow paced for a while, it still had a great plot. I was satisfied with the ending and overall I thought the book was great....more

Title: delirium
Author: lauren oliver
review: I read the book Delirium by Lauren Oliver. This book is about a society who has an operation or procedure that is performed once you are 18 that makeI read the book Delirium by Lauren Oliver. This book is about a society who has an operation or procedure that is performed once you are 18 that makes it so that you can’t love anymore. They think that love is dangerous and can get people in trouble. They think that their society is safer without love. It takes place in Portland, Oregon, during sometime in the future. The problem of the story is, Lena wants to follow the rules, but her friend, Hana just wants to break them. She convinces Lena to go to parties, listen to music, and even interact with boys, which eventually leads Lena to fall in love with Alex, a boy she met at a party.Lena develops throughout the text by the way that she thinks. In the beginning of the book, she talks a lot about her mom and how crazy she was. However, towards the end, she starts to view her mom as someone who maybe saw and understood things that most people didn’t. Lena starts to see these attributes in herself. She is also very worried and concerned with breaking the rules, because she just wants to live an average life and not be anything special. She doesn’t want to be out of the ordinary, but in the end of the book, she starts to realize how messed up her world is. She even allows herself to fall in love, which leads to all kinds of trouble. Lena interacts with other characters throughout the book by talking to them and openly sharing her opinions and thoughts with them.I could relate to Lena throughout the story because she just wants feels pressured to do things right and she doesn’t want to get in trouble. Lena doesn’t want to have to deal with anything that could keep her from getting the procedure. However, Lena starts to rebel and kind of not follow the rules, she is less uptight and just wants to have fun. She leaves her worries behind her and lets herself fall in love and have fun, even if it means she is breaking the rules. Although she starts to loosen up more, Lena does think about the people she loves a lot, like her mom, Hanna, and Alex. I like the way the book is written, because it shows the way that Lena feels and how her thoughts change over time. Overall, I really enjoyed reading this book, and I think that other people who enjoy romance novels would also like to read it....more

Title: to all the boys i've loved before
Author: jenny han
review: Lara Jean Covey writes love letters to the boys she has loved. She doesn’t mail them out, they are just for her to read. She writes them to 5 guys. OnLara Jean Covey writes love letters to the boys she has loved. She doesn’t mail them out, they are just for her to read. She writes them to 5 guys. One of the guys is her sisters recent ex boyfriend, and she writes a letter for him. One day she sees Peter Kavinsky walk up with her letter in his hand. He tells her that nothing will ever happen and then out of the corner of her eye she sees Josh--her sisters ex boyfriend--walking up to her with his letter. She gets nervous and kisses Peter. After the kiss she runs away and they end up fake dating to make his ex girlfriend jealous. Lara Jean and Peter Kavinsky make a contract and she has to go to the Ski Trip with him. While they are fake dating she gets feelings for him.Some of the readers said that they liked the book to but they feel like it was not realistic and that it was too sappy. Some people said it was cheesy and not worth reading while others loved it. I loved it and I agree with the people who love the book too. I think this book was fantastically written.I love this book! Jenny Han did an amazing job writing this. I love the storyline and how you can relate to the characters emotions and feelings in this book. I didn’t want to put this book down. It was so good and I can’t wait to read the others. One thing I loved about this book was the end romance with Peter and Lara Jean. I love how they started out fake dating and ended loving each other. There really isn’t anything that I can think of that I didn’t like. I loved it!...more

Title: my story
Author: elizabeth smart
review: My book was about Elizabeth Smart and her story. She got kidnapped and held hostage for nine months when she was only 14 years old. The book describesMy book was about Elizabeth Smart and her story. She got kidnapped and held hostage for nine months when she was only 14 years old. The book describes her as in a living hell. She suffered everyday and didn’t know if she would make it to the end of the day. She was terrified and lived with fear of the unknown.The word I chose was taken. This is one of the most used words. She talks a lot about how she is being taken away from her family and from her freedom. The definition of taken is reach for and hold. I feel like this could go with the book because he reached out and took ahold of her. So in a way it correlates but on the other hand I feel like a better definition for the book would be to take possession or something.I loved this book. It was so good. It gave me a new outlook on the community we live in. It taught me that I can get through hard things and that I just need to have the strength and know that God has a plan for me. I feel like i would be super scared and I would be to weak to keep going. But she was so strong through this whole thing. I loved this story! It shows how strong she is!...more

Title: code name verity
Author: elizabeth wein
review: **spoiler alert** Julie Beaufort-Stuart is a prisoner for the Nazi Gestapo. Julie thinks that her friend Maddie is dead. Maddie is her best friend. Ma**spoiler alert** Julie Beaufort-Stuart is a prisoner for the Nazi Gestapo. Julie thinks that her friend Maddie is dead. Maddie is her best friend. Maddie ends up not being dead! Julie is writing a story and agrees to exchange information for more time to finish her story. She goes into a lot of detail but not enough for the military to use. Maddie is a pilot who dropped Julie off in France. Right before they landed it started to crash. This story is based during the early years of World War II.I feel like a theme for this book is friendship. Julie and Maddie friendship blossoms in this book and they both help each other out some way or another. In the book they come to realize they never would have met if it wasn’t for the war. They also work really well together. In the book they both say we make a sensational team. With their friendship the can accomplish really anything if they put there mind to it.I really like this book. I think that it was super well written and it is really interesting to read about. I think this book is an eye-opener and it helps me to understand where people come from and who they are. I loved learning about the war and more about aircraft carriers. It was a really intriguing book. I am so glad that I go to read this book for class!...more

Title: the girl with seven names
Author: hyeonseo lee
review: Kim Ji-hae was born in North Korea, but not to the man her mother loved. Her mother divorced and to appease the parents of the man she loved, her mothKim Ji-hae was born in North Korea, but not to the man her mother loved. Her mother divorced and to appease the parents of the man she loved, her mother changed her name to park Min-young. This book is about a girl who continually has to change her name to survive. She escapes Korea when she turns 18, thinking she will have just have fun and be back before authorities realize she has gone, but things do not go as planed.I would say her key word is freedom. the author often express what is is to be free. when she escapes to china she thinks she is free but she isn't really. when she makes it to south Korea she expresses how she is truly free to do as she wants, and how the concept scares her. Absence of subjection to foreign domination or despotic government, in North Korea the government controls everything.I liked this book a lot. It made me really sad to hear about the way things are in North Korea and all of them left me in disbelief. Most of them I couldn't fathom, like how Chinese police sent the people back to Korea even when they knew the people would be severely punished. such detail was given of the famine I was left in utter disbelief. This book was truly amazing....more

Title: ready player one
Author: ernest cline
review: For English class, I chose to read the novel Ready Player One by Ernest Cline. The story is set in 2045 when the world is on the brink of collapse. ThFor English class, I chose to read the novel Ready Player One by Ernest Cline. The story is set in 2045 when the world is on the brink of collapse. The main character Wade Watts finds refuge in the OASIS, a virtual world allowing him to forget the one he is in. The creator of the OASIS, James Halliday recently died, leaving behind a contest to retrieve his fortune and claims to the OASIS company. The contest includes several puzzles and clues used to unlock three gates and ultimately find the prize. When Wade becomes the first person to find the copper key, the race begins, and players are willing to do anything to reach it. The novel is loaded with references to TV shows, movies, video games, technology, and sci-fi of the 80s-the time when Halliday was a kid.After reading Ready Player One, I read some reviews from other readers. All the characters are flawed in some way or other, but the novel does a good job of turning it around and bringing out some of their redeeming qualities. Some readers claimed it was unbearable to see kids in the 2040s reliving the 80s. I felt the book glorified the 80s a little too much, and it seemed like everyone went along with it as if they did not have a mind of their own. Some readers pointed out that Ernest Cline really knows his stuff, being someone who experienced the era. Though I found myself in information overload, I enjoyed it because it demonstrates a fan making a tribute to his ideal time period. One reviewer pointed out that the writing of the first half was flat, and many references were merely name-drops. I agree with this statement, because there are numerous occasions he mentions something and never brings it up again. One review stated that Cline made an observation that our world is heading toward a future with increasing loneliness and a digital world more vital than reality. I feel this is true, as it seems our civilization is heading farther from face-to-face interaction and more to virtual reality and more online relationships. Another review I found brought up Wade’s unhealthy relationship with Art3mis. I felt he became a stalker after their break up, and he tried to make her feel bad about her decision. I think this resulted from their solely online relationship, the Egg hunt, and his obsession of her.I had a great time reading this novel. Though I did not grow up in the 80s, I have had several influences from that era, and am familiar with some of the movies and music. I loved the elements of the contest incorporating old arcade games. I enjoyed how deep the book delved into the culture, exploring things such as anime and TV shows. I found the characters interesting, with some surprises along the way as the characters met each other in person. However, I felt the novel was almost one-sided at times, and things tended to blend together into seemingly nonessential facts about the 80s. Wade as a character had a sufficient background, but I would have liked to see more about Art3mis and others. I also found Wade’s break-in of the IOI headquarters slightly unbelievable. I found the battle between the Sixer forces and the Gunters at Anorak Castle was momentous, and I loved how it incorporated old anime mecha such as the Leopardon and Mechagodzilla. I also found it exciting to see the Wade use the Ultraman Beta Capsule. The read went by fast, and it maintained interest until the end. There were a couple plot twists, and I found the relationship between Art3mis and Wade different than I expected...more

Title: the princess saves herself in this one
Author: amanda lovelace
review: The main idea of this book is opposition and finding strength to overcome it. The beginning shows the pain and heartache she went through as a child iThe main idea of this book is opposition and finding strength to overcome it. The beginning shows the pain and heartache she went through as a child in relation to family and self image. As the story progresses and more things seemed to go wrong, her anger seems to increase as well. This anger stems from those close to her dying and betraying her. At one point in the book, she falls in love and her tone becomes less depressed and more lighthearted. The last section of this text is written in a second person style wherein the author expresses the ability we all have to overcome our trials.The book is obviously filled with poetic devices. The author uses a fair amount of cacophony in the beginning of the book, showing her struggles and pain as a child. She used this device to express her anger with her neglectful mother and her struggles with weight and self disgust. When she meets the man she loves, she uses more euphony in her writing as a result. Some of her writing is metaphorical including one poem in which she describes freckles as a universe. The title itself is a poetic device, foreshadowing the fact that her story gets better and she does begin to find herself.I didn’t really like this book. It was annoying to me that the author covered the front in, “the Princess Saves Herself in this One” then proceeds to write about how her boyfriend “saved” her. I understand anger and frustration, but the tone of this book came across as kind of petty sometimes. I respect the pain she went through and the strength it took to overcome her trials, but I don’t love how she so fully blamed the world. All she seemed to do was feel sorry for herself. I think she did have good reason to feel hurt and sad, but her reactions seemed petty and childish instead of trying to find something to do any real good. While that is how I feel about it, I also understand some people cope that way and I believe if it helped the author to overcome her struggles, it’s good....more

Title: geekerella
Author: ashley poston
review: Elle is a senior in high school who lives with her stepmom and stepsisters after the death of her father. The one thing she really cares about is StarElle is a senior in high school who lives with her stepmom and stepsisters after the death of her father. The one thing she really cares about is Starfield, an old science fiction tv show that her dad had loved. Darian is a highly popular tv actor who Elle despises and when he takes the role as the main character in the new movie adaptation of Starfield, she is not happy. However annoying he may seem, there is more to him than there appears. By mistake, the movie star begins texting Elle. As they get to know each other over the phone, both get increasingly attached to each other.The romance is partially realistic, but in a lot of ways it isn’t. Although it is possible to develop a crush on someone over text, oftentimes it makes real-life interaction awkward and stilted. At least if that’s how you got to know the other person. Where it is possible for a movie star and a normal girl to have a relationship, it isn’t particularly probable. However improbable this book would be, it doesn’t really make me dislike it because after all it is a modern adaptation of a fairytale.This book was fun. There wasn’t much depth and it didn’t impact me at all, but it was a fun read. If one is looking for something purely for entertainment, this is a good choice. I didn’t love it and I didn’t hate it. I liked it alright. Chick flicks are not my go to, but if they were I would probably like this book better....more

Title: code name verity
Author: elizabeth wein
review: **spoiler alert** Code Name Verity is the story of two friends who are separated in Nazi occupied France during World War II. The first, Verity, is a**spoiler alert** Code Name Verity is the story of two friends who are separated in Nazi occupied France during World War II. The first, Verity, is a special operative for the British military. Maddie, her best friend, is a pilot. When the two are shot down over France, Verity soon finds herself captured by Nazis. Tortured and interrogated for weeks, she makes a plea agreement which requires her to write a volume of pages that covers her time in the British army. Her papers give insight into the friendship that developed between herself and Maddie.The novel provides powerful themes centered around love and friendship. It highlights the fact that love often requires sacrifice and can lead to pain. It accentuates selflessness and what it can lead to. Throughout the book, Verity appears self serving and weak because she gives information to the Nazis. However, readers discover that she suffered immense pain and was willing to die for her cause. This cause was her original mission, destroying the hotel where she and other prisoners were held. In addition to Verity, Maddie shows selfless love at a pivotal moment in both her and Verity’s life.I literally bawled while reading this book. In my philosophy, if a book doesn’t leave you better when you finish it, it isn’t worth reading. I love books that make me think and feel--this one certainly fit the requirements. It drove me to ask myself who people really are and if I’m fair in my view of them. In Code Name Verity, every character had a story. Elizabeth Wein creates people who aren’t meant to be hated. They’re meant to be real. For example, even the Nazi captain has moments of humanity. Readers can see his uncertainty when it comes to his daughter. The book pushed me to question my own selflessness towards those I love. The scene that probably touched me more than any other, was one in which Maddie confesses to Verity’s brother, Jamie. Of all the people I love most in the world, my brother is very near the top, so this moment hit me especially hard. Jamie’s love and forgiveness is tear-jerking. I really appreciate this book. I do wish one could just skip through the first two thirds of it, while still understanding the context. Truthfully though, it was worth the slow beginning....more

Title: a little life
Author: hanya yanagihara
review: Ich habe das Buch angefangen zu lesen und schon nach 30 Seiten keine Lust mehr darauf verspürt. Um dem Ganzen eine Chance zu geben, bin ich auf´s HörbIch habe das Buch angefangen zu lesen und schon nach 30 Seiten keine Lust mehr darauf verspürt. Um dem Ganzen eine Chance zu geben, bin ich auf´s Hörbuch umgestiegen. Und das ich mir das bis zur letzten Minute angetan habe, ist nur der unglaublich guten Vertonung durch Torben Kessler geschuldet. Dem Mann höre ich einfach gern zu.Eins vorweg: Ich mag emotionale Bücher. Ich mag Bücher mit einer schweren Thematik. Ich mag Bücher, die zum Nachdenken anregen und auch meine Sicht auf die Dinge verändern. Ich mag auch Bücher, die Krankheiten thematisieren; insbesondere psychische Erkrankungen. Aus diesen Gründen habe ich zu diesem Buch gegriffen.Und ich fand es tatsächlich interessant, wie Judes psychische Erkrankung dargestellt wurde. So sehr ich manchmal auch genervt von ihm war, konnte ich seine Denk- und Handlungsweise durchaus nachvollziehen. Psychisch Kranke geben nunmal nicht gern zu, dass sie krank sind. Sie reden sich gern ein, dass sie gewisse (gute) Dinge einfach nicht verdienen. Sie meinen, sich immer selbst bestrafen zu müssen. Und es ist unfassbar schwer, an so einen Mensch ranzukommen, geschweige denn ihm helfen zu können.Mir war das Buch allerdings von Anfang an viel zu langatmig erzählt. Außerdem wurde die Handlung zunehmend unrealistisch. Das ganze Buch habe ich als eine schlichte Aneinanderreihung von Grausamkeiten empfunden. Das wurde irgendwann so unsinnig, dass ich das Ganze gar nicht mehr ernst nehmen konnte. Spätestens ab dem Kapitel, in dem man die Ursache für Judes Gehbehinderung erfährt, hab ich nur noch mit dem Kopf geschüttelt. Und ja, ich habe mir oft die Frage gestellt, was im Leben der Autorin passiert sein mag, dass sie das Bedürfnis verspürte, so eine Geschichte niederzuschreiben und einer fiktiven Person so viele Grausamkeiten anzutun.Auch stört mich, dass es in dem Buch nur schwarz und weiß gibt. In seiner Kindheit begegnet Jude fast nur Menschen, die böse sind. Die seine Schwäche ausnutzen und ihm nur schlimme Dinge antun. Da ist kein einziger Mensch, bei dem er Schutz findet. Zumindest nicht in dem Maße, wie man sich das für ein Kind wünscht. Und plötzlich ist er erwachsen und schon sind die bösen Menschen verschwunden. Plötzlich sind (fast) alle gut zu ihm. Wollen ihn als Freund, lieben ihn und zeigen ihm, wie wertvoll er ist.Und ich finde es schade, dass über all die Jahrzehnte, die man das Leben von Jude und seinen Freunden begleitet, eigentlich nie auf eine Lösung hingearbeitet wird. Alle schauen dabei zu, wie Jude an seinen Seelenqualen zugrunde geht und sich selbst verletzt. Andy flickt ihn immer wieder zusammen, aber auch er kommt nur ab und an mal mit dem erhobenen Zeigefinger um die Ecke. Oder Jude wird mal angeschrien, wenn er es mit seiner Ritzerei zu sehr übertrieben hat. Ja, es ist schwer, so einem Mensch zu helfen, wenn er das selbst nicht möchte. Aber tatenlos dabei zusehen kann doch auch nicht die Lösung sein.Was will mir das Buch also im Endeffekt sagen? Das die Welt voller perverser, pädophiler Männer ist? Dass der Freitod die einzige Lösung ist, wenn man mit seinen psychischen Problemen nicht klarkommt?Ich wünsche jedem, der das Buch mag, dass er für sich etwas aus der Geschichte mitnehmen konnte. Ich kann leider gar nichts daraus mitnehmen. Von daher ist es entgegen meiner Erwartung einfach kein Buch für mich und ich persönlich würde auch niemandem empfehlen, das Buch zu lesen. Title: red rising
Author: pierce brown
review: Red Rising by Pierce Brown is a science fiction novel. This book is a part of a series of books, called the Red Rising Series. In this universe, man-kRed Rising by Pierce Brown is a science fiction novel. This book is a part of a series of books, called the Red Rising Series. In this universe, man-kind has become interplanetary, and to maintain order, people have been split into genetically altered colors, with each color being genetically modified for their ‘purpose’. In this hierarchy, the Golds are at the top, with the Reds at the bottom. Every colors’ purpose is to serve the Golds in different ways, and Reds are the poorest of the poor. In this series, a young man and the main character Darrow goes from being a Red to a Gold, with the resolve to take down this hierarchy.To do this, Darrow has modifications to his body to become as strong and powerful as a Gold, but only because his willpower was strong enough for him not to die in the process. However, Darrow has to battle his mixed feelings of guilt and pleasure while having to adjust and befriend the Golds that now surround him. Will Darrow prevail against the tricks the Golds play on him, or will he become one of them?Overall, the best aspects of this book are its imagery, attention to detail, and realistic character development. On top of this, the author deploys these aspects in a manner that contributes to the story at a maximum volume. Because of this, I rate this book 5 stars....more

Title: once there were wolves

review: When an author can create as much empathy (if not more) for the animals revolving within this story as the characters, you know you’re reading somethiWhen an author can create as much empathy (if not more) for the animals revolving within this story as the characters, you know you’re reading something special.And this truly is special.Relatability to the ever growing problem we face with climate change and the landscapes we are losing are ever so present and everlasting, notably after the final page. This story really stays with you. The efforts Inti goes to reflect in her love for the cause she presents - to protect these wolves and allow them to change the land.I absolutely adored Once There Were Wolves. Not only not being able to leave the book alone, it seems to have left a lasting impression and growing eagerness for more within in the subject. Now the hope that Charlotte McConaghy revisits more of this in her future of writing grows and grows.For whoever is about to read this for the first time, I envy you immensely. This will be reread repeatedly. PHENOMENAL read and a real gem of a book. 12/10...more

Title: cold days
Author: jim butcher
review: I think Jim Butcher himself would admit that this series got off to a rough start, but over the years, his ability to weave an interesting story and hI think Jim Butcher himself would admit that this series got off to a rough start, but over the years, his ability to weave an interesting story and his writing style have improved immeasurable. His "Codex Alera" series is also evidence of that. The novels of the "Dresden Files" have successively increased in quality since "Storm Front", and this one has certainly not broken the pattern. "Cold Days" is Butcher's best novel yet. Harry Dresden and his compatriots have become well-developed, nuanced characters with personalities as subtle and complex as yours and mine. Butcher continues to take classic themes and villains of the fantasy genre and transition them smoothly into the contemporary era, as well as anthropomorphizing the superhuman. In "Cold Days", Butcher throws Dresden into yet another horrific circumstance to deal with, and just when we think Harry has got things under control, crazy twists happen. Butcher yet again throws curveballs that draw on plot elements across the entire series. If these twists weren't planned in advance, all the more credit to Butcher for telling captivating stories while keeping the series contiguous.This book, like the rest of the series (yes, including "Storm Front",) is a worthwhile, exciting read, leaving the reader exhilarated and drooling for more....more

Title: ready player one
Author: ernest cline
review: Very entertaining and absorbing. A lot of his thematic elements are things sci-fi enthusiasts will find familiar and comfortable, such as alternate reVery entertaining and absorbing. A lot of his thematic elements are things sci-fi enthusiasts will find familiar and comfortable, such as alternate reality, invasions, and finding happiness in dystopian futures. He integrates these devices in an original way, creating a picture of the future which may not be as far off as we think. This novel is an excellent satire of how technology and escapism are merging in our time. Also, it is a captivating and exciting read. The beginning is a little bit slow to read; he spends a lot of time setting up the story. It picks up pretty quickly though. I read this book in one sitting, primarily because I couldn't put it down....more

Title: the truth about alice
Author: jennifer mathieu
review: Just to preface I was chosen by the lovely people from Fierce reads to be on the Alice street team. Therefore I was given access to a copy through NetJust to preface I was chosen by the lovely people from Fierce reads to be on the Alice street team. Therefore I was given access to a copy through Net galley . This is my honest review and reflects only my personal opinions regarding the novel.This novel delves into the gritty underbelly the malicious high school gossip and achieves this by giving us us the perspective of four different students connected to the main character Alice who is the epicenter of the rampant rumors. The torment and the tension that surrounds Alice feels authentic and the voices of the rotating povs are distinct. The one small flaw however was that that every element also limits the reader's connection and investment to the characters.I give it four stars for the powerful message it delivers and the very clever way it goes about doing so. People judge Alice by the fragments of feelings that they take from their peers, and the reader is placed in that very role in which they must discern what kind of person Alice truly is from the thoughts and actions of of the 4 povs....more

Title: this is what happy looks like
Author: jennifer e. smith
review: Spoiler free!I loved the author's previous book, The Statistical Probability of Love at First Sight" so when I heard about this one I had to read it.ISpoiler free!I loved the author's previous book, The Statistical Probability of Love at First Sight" so when I heard about this one I had to read it.It was a cute read, there was nothing that made me detest it by any means. It lived up to the promise of a cute story, but compared to The Statistical Probability of Love at First Sight, it was a bit boring. I think the main issue in the book was the pacing, there were these interesting elements of love, family and secrets but, it never really came to a satisfying climax for me. it kind of sputtered into it's destination, yes some drama occurred but I was hoping for something with a bigger punch.On the plus side the characters are nice and rounded and I liked that it was not so wishy washy and that the two main character's Graham and Ellie had their own goals and hopes for their lives separate from the love aspect of the story. They also had their own familial struggles in the novel that helped to give them more dimension a reliability, I just wish that this was expanded on a bit.Overall it was a fun, quick read that does not bum the reader out, so it you are looking for something lighter but with mild character conflict then you will probably enjoy it.This Is What Happy Looks Like...more

Title: siege and storm
Author: leigh bardugo
review: As a very big fan of the first book in this series, Shadow and Bone I was eagerly counting down the days till the second installment in the Grisha triAs a very big fan of the first book in this series, Shadow and Bone I was eagerly counting down the days till the second installment in the Grisha trilogy was released.First off I thought the the cover art was beautiful and I am happy that they kept the same style as Shadow and Bones cover. Nothing trips me out more than having differing cover art style amongst book in a series!The Plot- Without giving any major plot twists away ( and believe me there are a lot of juicy ones!) the reader in thrown into a very rich Fantasy, in which our heroine Alina must take on very dire circumstances to ensure her safety. There is a lot of build to the third act but the pacing is good and does not drag. The character's that we met in the first novel have grown and evolved (some in good ways and others not so much). Mal is fleshed out even more and this adds some nice dimension to his and Alina's burgeoning relationship.My favorite elements of this however were the new characters that we meet along Alina's journey, many of whom are not what they claim to be. This added a whole new layer of intrigue. Additionally I enjoyed the whole political game element , that although mentioned in the first book is given a grand introduction in this sequel. Lastly the Darkling is most definitely back and brings massive amounts of drama and questionable actions with him ,as you do when you are a massively mysterious character.The entirety of the novel has action, big reveals and good character conflict, which I appreciated since many second instalments in trilogies suffer form the cursed "second book syndrome" although the Author uses the page space in Siege and Storm to set up the finale the book does not suffer under that weight.I gave it 5/5 stars for character growth,enjoyable/ steady plot progression . For fans of the Fire and Thorns trilogy, and the Throne of Glass series....more

review: I looked forward to reading but, was sadly disappointed in this book . He saved food for others, especially his love interest, but, some of the story just did not add up and that bothered me. I wish I could have felt more empathy for what he was going through - where was his compassion for others? He seemed a bit too happy to be a Jewish male at Auschwitz. I'm glad I read this book - it is not a time that should ever be forgotten....more

Title: the language of flowers
Author: vanessa diffenbaugh
review: This was a very unique story about a young girl and her heartbreaking struggle to survive the foster care system. The story goes back and forth from wThis was a very unique story about a young girl and her heartbreaking struggle to survive the foster care system. The story goes back and forth from when Victoria was 10 to present day when she is 18 and on her own. She has always felt unworthy with a huge hole inside her longing for her place in the world and longing to feel loved. Victoria's only comfort is through flowers, they are her passion. She communicates best using the "language of flowers". There was an amazing wealth of information about flowers and their meanings in this book. The story comes full circle when Victoria is faced with motherhood and the overwhelming task of not knowing what to do, being all alone and knowing this is probably exactly what her own Mother may have faced when she had abandoned her as a baby. I loved this book and am so glad I read it!...more

Title: jackal
Author: erin e. adams
review: “A man and his shadow live in the trees. When they walk in time both are pleased. If one calls your name, or the other tempts you off path, you must i“A man and his shadow live in the trees. When they walk in time both are pleased. If one calls your name, or the other tempts you off path, you must ignore both or face your wrath.”Liz left her hometown as soon as she could and never looked back. She returns for her best friend’s wedding. When her niece, a young black girl, goes missing in the woods, a white rust belt town’s dark past is revealed. She’s not the first to go missing, and Liz starts to notice a pattern taking her back to her youth when her only black girlfriend also went missing, in these same woods. Every white person is a suspect, and, each is believable.A little horror mixed in with some supernatural and a critical examination of racism that still exists to the point that no one can be trusted.This is an incredible debut and I loved how different this book felt. Some have said unconventional and I think that’s a perfect description. It has that same eeriness of Such a Fun Age, and similar betrayal. Our main character does all the “wrong” things in a horror book but she really shows her strength and determination through it all in the name of black girls past, present, and future. I can’t wait to see what this author does next!(Not for the faint of heart. This book is descriptive about death)....more

Title: white horse
Author: erika t. wurth
review: Incredible book and incredible audio! One of my most anticipated books of the year and I LOVED it. A perfect release and read for Native American HeriIncredible book and incredible audio! One of my most anticipated books of the year and I LOVED it. A perfect release and read for Native American Heritage Month - Erika T. Wurth is an urban Native of Apache, Chickasaw, and Cherokee descent.Urban Indian Kari James has her life turned upside down when her cousin finds an old family bracelet that belonged to Kari’s deceased mother. The bracelet brings out Kari’s mother’s ghost, requiring Kari to confront her past in an effort to find out what really happened to her mother when she passed. It becomes a journey of self reflection and critical analysis on all of the relationships Kari has.So much nostalgia and great analysis of current social issues. Kari loves heavy metal, Stephen King, and beer. She made me think of my bestie. Social issues if MMIW, racial tensions with police, alcoholism, and more.Trust me, you will not regret stopping everything to read this book!Content warnings: death, addiction, rape...more

Title: ariadne
Author: jennifer saint
review: A debut, and a retelling of Ariadne, princess of Crete in Greek mythology. Ariadne helped Theseus defeat/kill her brother the Minatour and then fled tA debut, and a retelling of Ariadne, princess of Crete in Greek mythology. Ariadne helped Theseus defeat/kill her brother the Minatour and then fled the island with Theseus, betraying her family and especially her sister Phaedra who helped Theseus as well. But Theseus takes Ariadne to Naxos island and abandons her, leaving her alone with her thoughts. This retelling of Ariadne’s story really places a spotlight on the women of the stories and the realistic struggles that these women faced, some a lot like what women face to this day. The book was easy to get into, easy to stay with, and overall really enjoyable.I loved that womanhood was explored and will leave you with a quote:“I had hit upon a truth of womanhood: however blameless a life we led, the passions and the greed of men could bring us to ruin, and there was nothing we could do.”...more

Title: everything beautiful in its time

review: A beautiful memoir explaining how Jenna and her family have managed to get through grief. A quick read that I think a lot of people will find relatablA beautiful memoir explaining how Jenna and her family have managed to get through grief. A quick read that I think a lot of people will find relatable and enjoyable considering the times. I loved the discussion of Jenna’s love for her sister and how she always wanted more than one child so that they could experience having a sibling. Andrew and I always felt that way too - we value it so much. Jenna’s connection with all of her grandparents is so sweet, and not unlike my own. I really enjoyed that. I know how fortunate we are to have our grandparents in our lives still, and even more fortunate to have spent a lot of time with great grandparents as well.Favorite quote: “It isn’t courageous to do the right thing.” Barbara Bush (former First Lady). review: Another great audiobook. This life story is mind blowing. A true test of finding yourself is what you become despite the teachings, lifestyle choices,Another great audiobook. This life story is mind blowing. A true test of finding yourself is what you become despite the teachings, lifestyle choices, and habits of your parents. Tara explains her survivalist Mormon family in great detail and also her educational journey despite the lack of support from her family and challenges faced as a result of being raised in her family’s chosen world. I can’t imagine not going to school once in life before college. I also can’t imagine not having a birth certificate for nearly 10 years. The thing that struck me the most profound was that she recognized the clear, strict, separate paths that were laid out for men and women if she stayed and she chose that path that was not laid out for her. Title: the tattooist of auschwitz
Author: heather morris
review: **spoiler alert** A beautiful story, and I think it's the best story written out of them all.In school I was shown the boy in the stripped pyjamas wh**spoiler alert** A beautiful story, and I think it's the best story written out of them all.In school I was shown the boy in the stripped pyjamas which I found, personally, to show nothing of what the war was like and who was effected by it, like who ended up in the camps. Instead, we had a story of a poor German boy who died in the camp because he found a friend.This story does the opposite. It tells us the true story of Lale, about the love, the torture, and the people that he had to go through while he was at the camp. This story shows every part of what he had to go through and includes the story of his wife who he had met at the camp and who had survived the camp and how they had to find each other again after escaping auschwitz.The story also includes the before and after of the time he spent at the camp, and it's a sad and terrifying experience to read about.The book is so much better because it's coming from someone who had THE most inside knowledge of how the camp was run, who was in power, he had connections which he had to make in order to survive and help the other prisoners at the camp. He has told the story that will not only keep what had happened during the war alive but also will keep his love story alive for decades to come.I highly recommend this book and don't take the 3/5 as a negative sign, I'm very strict with my rating and this is a very high rating compared to the other books I have read. This book is going against some of the most famous and loved classics there are.Again, READ ITTT....more

I didn’t hate this book despite it making me really angry multiple times. Mostly the writing style and choices in the book.Author would be writing up to a pivotal moment and end the chapter just for the next chapter to start off in the future and look back on that moment in hindsight. Incredibly irritating as a reader. Many flashbacks. Too many.So. Much. Monologue. I found myself skimming some of it.I predicted the end around 50 pages in. The ending was not satisfying.I gave it three stars because I liked the idea and plot of this book, I just thought it could have been executed better. review: Pineapple Street is a very enjoyable, character-driven novel that I consumed quickly! My favorite Stockton family member is Sasha; I found her most rePineapple Street is a very enjoyable, character-driven novel that I consumed quickly! My favorite Stockton family member is Sasha; I found her most relatable and rooting for her throughout. I feel like Sasha could have played a bigger part in this story. The other characters were harder to connect with due to privilege, snobbery, and being out-of-touch. The Pineapple Street house represents something different to each character and the complex, family dynamics made this story difficult to put down. Georgiana is the most dynamic, yet least likable character in the book which provides a unique prospective. Jackson delivered a thoughtful, engaging story with many layers and I enjoyed reading it....more

Title: divine rivals
Author: rebecca ross
review: I don’t normally write reviews, but feel like I need to explain this one given the amazing reviews it has from seemingly everyone else.I was really exI don’t normally write reviews, but feel like I need to explain this one given the amazing reviews it has from seemingly everyone else.I was really excited about this book but the beginning dragged on then the relationship between the characters felt rushed and cliche as the book went on. I didn’t find it believable at all, but maybe it has to do with the age of the characters.While I liked the characters, in general they felt one dimensional and some even felt like different people in the first half of the book vs the second half. In the beginning Iris was independent if not stressed and frustrated with how her life was going, but by the end her entire life revolves around some guy??? And she was constantly afraid unless he was there to be strong and comfort/motivate her? No thanks.Also, for a book about a magical war between gods the only magical items we really got to see were typewriters. And even those weren’t critical to the story by the last third!The writing was lovely, but by the end I just wanted the book to be over. Gave it 2, could maybe see 2.5, but overall pretty disappointed. Ok, rant over....more

review: Now I love Ana, she did bring Josh and Jules, but she tends to use the same format for every single one of her books. This usually isn't a problem ifNow I love Ana, she did bring Josh and Jules, but she tends to use the same format for every single one of her books. This usually isn't a problem if the characters are interesting enough, but they in fact were NOT. The way Sloane's family was talking about her, I thought this girl killed someone or something interesting. But no she just can't cry and her ex cheated on her. Sad, but unoriginal. Xavier's story was even MORE unoriginal, if that is even possible. Do you know how many times I have sat through the story of "I killed my mom, it was an accident, but I blame myself". Title: carry on
Author: rainbow rowell
review: Carry on est un livre particulier : il est une fanfiction de « Simon Snow » écrit par Cath, l’héroïne de « Fanfiction »de Rainbow Rowell. Dans ce romaCarry on est un livre particulier : il est une fanfiction de « Simon Snow » écrit par Cath, l’héroïne de « Fanfiction »de Rainbow Rowell. Dans ce roman, on suit le quotidien de Cath lorsque sa vie connaît un grand changement : elle quitte le foyer familial pour faire ses études à la faculté. Sa sœur jumelle avec qui elle avait une relation très fusionnelle, refuse de partager une chambre avec elle. Cath se retrouve donc à devoir s’approprier un nouvel environnement, de nouveaux cours, de nouvelles relations sociales et amoureuses. Elle est fan d’une série de livres « Simon Snow » et en attendant la sortie du huitième et dernier tome, elle écrit une fanfiction à succès « Carry On ». L’histoire de Cath est alors entrecoupée de passages des livres « Simon Snow » et de sa fanfic, cela nous permettant de découvrir l’univers magique où évoluent Simon et son ennemi Baz. Lors de cette lecture, je m’étais fortement attachée au personnage de Cath, mais également à ceux de Simon et Baz. C’est donc avec plaisir que j’ai découvert leur univers ainsi que l’histoire finale « créée par Cath ».Le début du livre a été un peu déroutant pour moi, dans le sens où il a fallu s’approprier un univers que je ne connaissais pas alors qu’il est supposé être connu par « les lecteurs » de la fanfic de Cath. J’avoue que le fait d’avoir lu Fanfiction il y a deux ans de cela et de ne pas l’avoir relu avant « Carry On » ne m’a pas aidée… Cependant, Rainbow Rowell arrive à poser rapidement le fonctionnement du monde magique de Simon Snow, ainsi que les liens entre les personnages et les enjeux de l’histoire.L’univers de Simon Snow est fortement inspiré de la saga Harry Potter, on y découvre ainsi de nombreux points communs. Simon Snow est un orphelin « Normal », il n’a eu connaissance de ses pouvoirs magiques qu’à 11 ans, lorsque le Mage, « the Greatest Mage», le directeur de l’école de magie Watford fait de lui son héritier, lui révèle qu’il détient un grand pouvoir magique et le fait rentrer dans l’école pour ses études. Le monde de la magie est alors en guerre contre un ennemi particulier, « The Insidious Humdrum » (la monotonie rampante) qui tente de supprimer la magie en Angleterre. Pour autant, Simon Snow évolue dans un environnement très contemporain où les magiciens possèdent téléphones portables, télévisions, etc...Cependant, Simon se révèle un piètre magicien, il a du mal à jeter des sorts, comprendre le fonctionnement de la magie et la contrôler. Cependant, à des moments critiques, il est capable de réaliser des sorts révélant un grand pouvoir magique. A l’école, il est obligé de partager sa chambre avec Tyrannus Basilton Pitch, « Baz », soupçonné par Simon d’être un vampire et qui devient son pire ennemi. Simon devient très ami avec Penelope Bunce, une magicienne aux grands pouvoirs qui devient une alliée indispensable. Il a également une petite amie, Agatha Wellebelove.L’histoire de "Carry On" commence donc dans cet univers supposé être établi depuis 7 tomes. Le livre débute avec l’arrivée de Simon à Watford pour sa 8ème et dernière année. Cependant, son retour ne se passe pas comme prévu et Baz est anormalement absent.Tout au long du livre, les péripéties vont s’enchaîner jusqu’au final de la série telle qu’elle est imaginée par Cath. L’intrigue est assez complexe et les personnages ne sont pas manichéens, en proie à des décisions qui peuvent aller contre leur postulat de base. Le fait que les chapitres correspondent au point de vue des personnages permet de mieux les comprendre. Cependant, la psychologie d’un personnage, Agatha, me semble moins développée, moins logique. Mais j’explique cela par le fait qu’on est supposé lire une fanfic où l’auteure efface un peu ce personnage pour en mettre d’autres en avant.Au niveau de l’écriture, on découvre un vocabulaire parfois peu politiquement correct (fuck, etc…) qui détonne avec le vocabulaire qu’on lirait dans un livre jeunesse. On y découvre également de l’humour et des références, notamment dans les sorts jetés par les protagonistes : « Simon says » (la version anglaise « Jacques a dit »), « Have a break, have a kit-kat », « These aren’t the droids you’re looking for » (en référence à l’épisode 4 de Star Wars)... Et encore, je pense que mon niveau d’anglais ne m’a permis de comprendre tout l’humour présent dans le livre. Toutes ces libertés sont permises par la pseudo-écriture d’une fanfiction et cela est agréable à lire.Je retrouve en effet beaucoup de caractéristiques présentes dans les fanfics que j’ai lues à l’époque d’Harry Potter. Rainbow Rowell arrive ainsi parfaitement à utiliser les codes d’une fanfic pour donner beaucoup de crédibilité à son livre. On arrive à s’approprier rapidement l’histoire inexistante de 7 tomes et à prendre du plaisir à lire ce « faux » huitième tome.J’ai passé un moment de lecture agréable grâce à une intrigue complexe, des personnages intéressants. Je pense que mon avis est aussi lié à ma nostalgie : j’adorais lire et écrire des fanfics autour de Harry Potter avec des amis, en attendant la sortie des tomes de la saga. Je pense notamment à la fanfic « Les portes » de Alohomora dont j’attendais impatiemment la suite, mais également les fanfics de Lychee, les fanfics Harry/Malefoy, Severus/Sirius, etc…Carry on est un livre vraiment à part : un roman écrit pour être une fanfiction et qui est totalement réussi. Je pense cependant que pour bien apprécier ce livre, il est nécessaire d’avoir lu « Fangirl » auparavant....more

Title: fangirl
Author: rainbow rowell
review: Cather "Cath" Avery est passionnée par la série de livres "Simon Snow", à tel point qu'elle est en train d'écrire une fanfiction à succès en attendantCather "Cath" Avery est passionnée par la série de livres "Simon Snow", à tel point qu'elle est en train d'écrire une fanfiction à succès en attendant la sortie du dernier tome. Lorsque l'histoire commence, Cath fait son entrée à l'université et quitte ainsi son cocon familial. Ce passage de l'adolescence à l'âge adulte est d'autant plus difficile que sa soeur jumelle, Wren, aspire à plus d'indépendance et a refusé de partager sa chambre universitaire avec elle.On va ainsi suivre Cath lors de son année universitaire et partager avec elle son évolution entre cours, amis, amours, famille et fanfiction. Les relations aux autres sont décrites avec beaucoup de réalisme, comme on avait pu le découvrir dans Eleanor et Park (livre plus récent mais sorti avant Fangirl en France).Outre le caractère attachant de Cath, l'omniprésence de la fanfiction apporte un plus à cette lecture qu'on a envie de poursuivre sans s'arrêter.Je me suis ainsi replongée quelques années en arrière lorsque je lisais les nombreuses fanfictions autour de Harry Potter et que j'attendais impatiemment la suite de la fanfic "Les portes" écrite Alohomora...C'est donc avec plaisir que j'ai lu l'histoire de cette fangirl à l'université....more

Title: beauty queens
Author: libba bray
review: Reads back. 'Hmm... Interesting.'I read this as an audiobook from my public library. I gave Beauty Queens by Libba Bray - one of my favorite authorsReads back. 'Hmm... Interesting.'I read this as an audiobook from my public library. I gave Beauty Queens by Libba Bray - one of my favorite authors 4.5 stars because I love the theme and the message just not all the sexual things which weren't very many. The book was short and spicy. That sound wrong. Short and sassy. Better much better.Okay here's my review.50 girls are on a plane to a deserted island to host the Miss Teen Dream Beauty Pageant. The plane crashes and 13 survive. The 13 girls have to survive on a plane without food and water. The island has secrets and so do the girls.My favorite character is between the main character and a minor character. Adina and Tiara. I can relate to both despite Tiara's humorous stupidity. She was very dumb but very funny. You got to see as the book went on that she was more than just a girl who was stupid.The characters are very realistic and I want more. The story keep me guessing about what each girls secrets were and I would had never guessed that it was the secret it was. My favorite part was the ending. Not because it was over but because it was amazing and super funny. All the scenes were written beautifully. The book made me laugh a lot and brought me to tears. One of the best books I've read all year. I couldn't put it down.I found it difficult to like any of the other characters beside the main one at first but I think that was the point. When the Pirates came I didn't like the fact that Adina hooked up with someone she had JUST MET.I would suggest non homophobic teens to read this awesome and funny well written book. Libba Bray has not failed me yet. If you have a low romance tolerance this book is not for you. But still read it. Also for feminists everywhere.Libba bray is also the author of other series I recommend by her. Beauty Queens is a 9.8 stars out of 10 stars. I just didn't like all the romance to be honest....more

review: I really enjoyed Ali Hazelwood's writing and when I heard she was releasing a paranormal romance I was overjoyed and at the same time a bit skeptical,I really enjoyed Ali Hazelwood's writing and when I heard she was releasing a paranormal romance I was overjoyed and at the same time a bit skeptical, but I just finished reading this book and I'm so happy to say this book is amazing the paranormal element was well thought out and not too over the top, it was simple but the world was well built and easy to follow and it shows great promise for the future. Now when it comes to the romance, I absolutely loved it. It felt organic and genuine the way it went from a friendship to love in a way that was not rushed and felt honest, and as readers we were able to really feel the same emotions at the same time as our main characters. The main characters were really nice ans quite relatable and despite their own issues they were able to pull through and form something beautiful. The only reason this book is not a 5 star is because I wish the pacing was a bit better the beginning was a bit slow but all in all this book was an amazing experience, and I can't wait for more....more

review: À mon avis, every book should be read twice. I finished this book and fell in love with Ifemelu. I fell in love with her cynicism, her errors, her lovÀ mon avis, every book should be read twice. I finished this book and fell in love with Ifemelu. I fell in love with her cynicism, her errors, her love for Obinze, her everything. And this is not to say that I was romantically interested in her. Rather, I felt fully immersed in and in awe of her world. This is one of the great successes of this novel. When a character is the reader’s main motivation for turning the pages, and not the plot itself, then the author has truly brought a being to life — a difficult task. Upon my second reading of this book, I fell out of love with Ifem. How could she have done this to Ceiling? Why does she think she is different from high snobiety? She is just as rude towards the lesser as the American academics and well-to-do Nigerians that she criticizes. I found hypocrisy in Ifem everywhere. Where I had once felt empathetic joy at her natural hair journey, I scoffed and skipped a few pages. Wah wah. Because of the privilege that I had picked up on, Ifem’s struggles with identity and acceptance seemed so… superficial. And then I realized the other great success. There is depth to Ifemelu. It is this depth that makes this novel so incredible....more

Title: hyperbole and a half
Author: allie brosh
review: Don’t judge a book by its cover has never been truer than it is for this one – at least for me. When I first received this book, I didn’t think I’d reDon’t judge a book by its cover has never been truer than it is for this one – at least for me. When I first received this book, I didn’t think I’d really like it all that much but boy was I wrong. It was marvelous and pretty funny too. Both the writing and the drawings were clever and funny. There isn’t really a linear story, but instead Brosh looks back on and recounts stories from her childhood to adulthood while providing her present insight on those stories. Some chapters don’t even tell a story but instead are just her thoughts about her life and herself. The lack of a linear story and focus makes the book seem a bit choppy as it goes from chapter to chapter, but I think it works well because it seems to match her train of thought, and her voice. Speaking of her voice, though, Brosh has a great one! She is bittersweet and piercingly witty. Her voice was probably the highlight of the book for me. She really had me cracking up, especially in the “Goose Dinosaur” chapter, the hot sauce chapter, and the cake chapter, and the ones about her dogs. Okay, I picked out a large majority of the book there. That tells you just how funny I thought it was. Her drawings were perfect matches for the stories as well and were also just as funny. Beyond the humor, Brosh also approaches huge topics in her book questioning identity, looking into her depression and personality introspectively. She sort of forces you to consider your own identity as she so openly explores her own....more

Title: brown girl dreaming
Author: jacqueline woodson
review: Brilliant novel. I could have kept reading if there were more pages. I wanted more pages, to see how Jacqueline’s story continued. This book was, agaiBrilliant novel. I could have kept reading if there were more pages. I wanted more pages, to see how Jacqueline’s story continued. This book was, again, not my typical selection but it became a wonderful read. I loved watching Jacqueline grow up and develop as a person as well as a young writer. She had such an interesting but sincere voice and her personality, memories, and thoughts were all displayed so well throughout the pages of the novel. Beyond the captivating story, it also included so much depth and history. Everything in this novel just felt so unique yet very real and authentic at the same time. I recognized a lot of the injustices she witnessed in her lifetime and felt as if I was learning a lot from this very young character whose voice, again, was just so brilliantly rendered. Although I didn’t live through anything like her in regards to the time period or the oppression, I was able to appreciate the ways in which she showed them to us readers. I loved the parts in the South because I, too, had many similar experiences growing up in a more Southern, country location. It was beautifully described as the “home” I’ve always known and loved. Speaking of “homes,” though, it was also interesting to see how her young character explored and negotiated this idea of “home,” and what makes a place a home. It was a great topic that really had me thinking about my own homes. Lastly, I loved the way this novel was written with the haikus and the poetry. Again, it was so unique feeling.On the last page of the novel she brings up all of these pieces of her life and says “All the worlds you are…gather into one world called You” and that truly is the essence of this great novel (320). She tells her story, inevitably encouraging you, as the reader, to consider your own story, your own homes, your worlds that gather into one world called You. I simply loved it....more

Title: eleanor & park
Author: rainbow rowell
review: The entire time I read this book, I couldn’t help but think about how my little sister would love it. Down to the cover, it seems like the perfect novThe entire time I read this book, I couldn’t help but think about how my little sister would love it. Down to the cover, it seems like the perfect novel for a younger girl who swoons over a sappy love story. It almost calls out to young girls. Described as a young adult novel, I can see its appeal to the teen or maybe even the youngest adult. I mean, it’s pretty relatable to someone growing up and it offers a look into what almost all young girls dream about, young love. But there are also the cliché “cliques” with the mean girls/guys, the high school drama, the low self esteem issues that are common in any coming of age novel, and of course, that eye-rolling love story I mentioned. These very elements make the novel feel somewhat relatable to anyone, but especially the younger audiences. However, in some ways it also felt a bit too mature for the intended audience. The language was often harsh and there were frightening abusive moments in the novel. It is true that several young people go through these issues as well, but I guess I felt it to be beyond both Eleanor’s and any young person’s maturity. In the end, it wasn’t my favorite novel ever. To be fair, though, it isn’t a novel I would typically read and I felt a lot of the dialogue/plot to be cheesy, overdone, and unrealistic. I wouldn’t necessarily recommend the novel either but I will say that I understand its appeal to the younger audience - of ladies especially....more

Title: the marriage plot
Author: jeffrey eugenides
review: (Contains Potential Spoilers- Read Cautiously)It's hard for me to muster the right words when reviewing this book. As I read the book, I was first and(Contains Potential Spoilers- Read Cautiously)It's hard for me to muster the right words when reviewing this book. As I read the book, I was first and foremost extremely grateful that I just so happened to have double majored in English and Religious Studies in undergrad. I say this because of the large amount of name dropping and theory that is discussed with little introduction behind them. If it hadn’t been for my own educational background, I wouldn’t have recognized much of what Eugenides brought into the novel let alone appreciate some of the ideas and moments that I could actually relate to as a student of those disciplines. Still, there were moments I didn’t recognize names or ideas and realized how that might be the case entirely for other readers of the novel. I’m glad I was able to find some appreciation in some of those instances where other readers might have felt alienated.Nonetheless, I am a sucker for a good story in any medium so I read expecting to get one out of this novel. It kept me relatively interested some of the time, but as I read the final page in the novel, I realized I hadn’t gotten the story I was hoping for. I had sort of been rooting for Mitchell for awhile being the character that had developed more authentically in my eyes and yet, the novel has a pretty unsatisfying ending which left me wondering what the purpose was for much of the seemingly redundant, excessively unnecessary details throughout the entire novel. In the end, my greatest take away from this novel is that Madeleine, a main character who is a woman, is heading off to be independent and presumably successful in academia, which was nice after seeing her be tirelessly dependent while suppressing her intelligence and talents through much of the novel. Seeing her break away from that repressive state of living was refreshing. Still, I guess I wanted more out of this novel and I just didn’t quite get it.The novel does, though, offer interesting looks into mental illness, religion, gender roles and challenges, education, drug and alcohol abuse, consequence, and much, much more. In the almost 800-page novel, many, many, issues are brought to light briefly while others stay present throughout the entirety novel. I almost wish there had been less in order to have focused on the few, more – if that makes sense. It’s as if this book attempts to tackle too much at once, rather than focus strongly on a few important ideas....more

Title: we were liars
Author: e. lockhart
review: Book Review of We Were Liars by E. LockhartIn this Realistic Fiction/Romance Drama, I deduced a major lesson that all of us could learn: The characteBook Review of We Were Liars by E. LockhartIn this Realistic Fiction/Romance Drama, I deduced a major lesson that all of us could learn: The characterization of a family by a group of people may not always be true especially when a perfect family is far from what is considered to be perfect. A lesson like this is important for people who become jealous of the rich as there is not a single person who doesn’t go through something.Cadence Sinclair is the eldest grandchild of the wealthy and esteemed Sinclair family. She is of 3 older children of the Sinclair family: her cousins Johnny and Mirren. Along with these three, there is a child named Gat who lives with Johnny as his uncle is in a relationship with Johnny’s mother. Together, these four make up the “Liars”. Within Cadence’s fourteenth summer, or “Summer 14”, Gat and Cadence fall in love. However, it is later found out during Cadence’s fifteenth summer that Gat is dating someone else.Cadence decides one summer evening to go out for a swim and hits her head on a rock. This event leads to her having chronic, severe headaches that eventually lead her getting addicted to Percocet, a pain-relieving drug used to fight her headaches. Her mother, perceivably wanting to avoid her daughter’s troubles, forces her daughter to go on a Europe trip with her father during her sixteenth summer. Upon returning to the island in Cadence’s seventeenth summer, much had changed to the island including the estates and the people in them. Inheritance became a struggle between the daughters of the patriarch of the family, Harris, and the daughters were having their kids suck up to Harris. Not wanting their family to fall apart, Cadence and the other Liars hatch up a drastic plan.I found the book to be a bit too slow-paced. The format of the book allotted for time skips occurring between every couple of chapters which made it seem like a lot of time was going by without anything of importance occurring; not to mention the fact that very little got done to resolve the conflict until the end of the book. To your average reader, including myself, this becomes very annoying and makes the book very boring. However, it must be noted that much of the book was spent with Cadence trying to collect what happenedRegarding what I found to be one of the themes of the book, I felt that the author was very able to communicate what it was. First, on the first page of the book, Cadence states, “WELCOME TO THE beautiful Sinclair family. No one is a criminal. No one is an addict. No one is a failure.” (1) Already, she is stating that she has a perfect family because she puts this facade that nothing is wrong with her family. It is known that this statement is a facade because the author, through the voice of Cadence, hints at the major events that occur throughout the book “It doesn’t matter if divorce shreds the muscles of our hearts so that they will hardly beat without a struggle. It doesn’t matter if trust-fund money is running out; if credit card bills go unpaid on the kitchen counter. It doesn’t matter if there’s a cluster of pill bottles on the bedside table. It doesn’t matter if one of us is desperately, desperately in love. So much in love[,] that equally desperate measures must be taken”(1). Such a family that is described by Cadence would not have these problems if they were beautiful or for lack of a better term, perfect. However, when Cadence tells us of these problems, she sarcastically tells us this by using the phrase “It doesn’t matter” as if to say that despite these things, her family is still perfect. Furthermore, the fact that she thinks the family is perfect at all is not true because towards the end of the first page she states this, “We are Sinclairs. No one is needy. No one is wrong. We live, at least in the summer, on a private island off the coast of Massachusetts. Perhaps that is all you need to know”(1). Saying that “Perhaps that is all you need to know” means that we as an audience may only need to know that the Sinclairs are the things that are shown in this quote. As we are not a part of the family, we have no reason to care about what goes on within the family thus not having to care about the truth of what goes on in the family besides the superficial things that the family presents itself to be. This ties directly to the theme of “The characterization of a family by a group of people may not always be true especially when a perfect family is far from what is considered perfect” because we as the audience before reading this book would have thought that the Sinclair family was perfect just because we only got to see the surface level characteristics. However, by just reading the book and even these quotes, we get to understand the true nature of the Sinclair family and how imperfect they are.The author was able to communicate this theme through her use of the characters of the story. Mainly, she used a character named Gat and another character, his uncle Ed, to share how imperfect the perfect family of Sinclair is. Firstly, the subtle bigotry that came from Harris, the patriarch of the family, was shown throughout the book; a characteristic like this is not something the Sinclair family should have when Cadence says, “We are old-money Democrats.”(1) Modern Democrats, even old-money Democrats, shouldn’t have an ounce of bigotry in the blood. Harris’ bigotry’s influence becomes apparent when Carrie, one of Cadence’s aunts, refuses to marry Ed in the fear of losing her inheritance, “‘That’s the thing,’ said Gat. ‘Everyone’s always asking Harris about everything. Why should a grown woman have to ask her father to approve her wedding?’/ ‘Granddad wouldn’t stop her.’[said Cadence}/ ‘No,’ said Gat. ‘But back when Carrie first moved in with Ed, Harris made it clear that all the money earmarked for her would disappear if she married him.[ ]The point is, Harris doesn’t like Ed’s color. He’s a racist bastard, and so was Tipper.’”() The author often uses Gat as a spearhead to question the accuracy of the perception that everyone has of the Sinclair family. In this instance, she is using Gat to question the notion that the family is rich as a whole. He makes us aware that the control of the money is centered only on one person, the patriarch, and that all of his daughters have to appease him in order to keep their inheritance. Another example of her use of Gat was when he talks about the true definition of the Sinclairs as a beautiful family, “He knows he’s not supposed to be that guy. He’s a Democrat, he voted for Obama—but that doesn’t mean he’s comfortable having people of color in his beautiful family.”() What Gat references is Harris’ true belief of what is considered to be a beautiful family, in that, the entire family is ethnically homogeneous: white. Harris worries that if Gat and Gat’s uncle, the people of color in which Gat is referencing, become a part of the Sinclair race, it will ruin his “beautiful” family. As readers, before reading the book, we thought that the Sinclair family was described to be beautiful because they were all attractive; we now know that they are meant to be beautiful because the family has no variation in their ethnicities. While the author described Gat as political, and he surely was so, she didn’t overuse him to the point where he was only political. He was the romantic interest of the main character, and he was her emotional anchor.While this book was clever in delivering its message, it did not change any of my opinions or views. This is because it shares the same views as I do in relation to the income inequalities we experience on our planet. I do not find it fair that the rich can get away with murder(figuratively) and the average person cannot.This book was able to make me think a lot because of how unstraightforward it was. I understand that the speaker was unreliable, and that I had to take what she said with a grain of salt. As a result, I’m only willing to recommend this book to people who like to think.With all of what I said in mind, I would give this book 4 stars....more

Title: how music got free
Author: stephen richard witt
review: This was a cool read. As someone who grew up throughout the CD to pirating to legal mp3 to streaming period, it was fascinating to see what was goingThis was a cool read. As someone who grew up throughout the CD to pirating to legal mp3 to streaming period, it was fascinating to see what was going on behind the scenes of all of this. Especially from the pirating side. I honestly had no clue that the near entirety of Napster's files originated with basically a handful of people.The best part of this book is definitely the ongoing discussion about the changing economy of music. How music companies made money in the 80s and 90s is outrageously different from how they make money now. It's so interesting to think that pirating music created such a different music culture that's still incredibly profitable. Wonderful study into changing economies.Great read.
