Title: essentialism
Author: greg mckeown
review: Solid book. I dug that it has great ideas and actionable next steps. The concept of doing less is something I honestly aspire to. I often find myselfSolid book. I dug that it has great ideas and actionable next steps. The concept of doing less is something I honestly aspire to. I often find myself over-committing, and as someone who never wants to deliver less-than-stellar work, that's a problem. To do your best, you need to commit all of yourself, and take care of yourself completely, and that takes time. It means you can't do everything, nor should you try, and instead you need to focus on what's most important. That's a much trickier process than it sounds, and that's where this book comes into play.A mentor recommended this one to me, and I'm super grateful that she did. Definitely recommend for anyone who often finds themselves stretched too thin....more

Title: eleanor oliphant is completely fine
Author: gail honeyman
review: This is a great little exploration into an interesting mind. I absolutely loved it. The character Eleanor drives the whole thing, and it starts out soThis is a great little exploration into an interesting mind. I absolutely loved it. The character Eleanor drives the whole thing, and it starts out so bizarrely fascinating that it grabs you. It turned out much much for heartwarming than I originally expected. And honestly, I felt like I predicted the ending toward the middle. But that’s not bad, it’s honestly nice to start coming up with theories about a character and a story, and being confirmed right at the end while also coming away super hopeful and positive.As out there as this book is - and honestly, when you get past the heartwarming, there really is a strong ‘bizarre’ undertone - it was much more relatable than I ever imagined it would be. The mind’s a fascinatingly powerful thing, and highs and lows are very real. I totally dig how much the story dove into that.Great book, 100% definitely recommend. Instant classic.Also, I want to document that it felt nice to finish this book on Mental Health Awareness Day. Nice little coincidence....more

review: Far and away, this is my favorite Ruth Ware book so far. My last two reads of hers were both good, but lacked great endings. This one remedies that, aFar and away, this is my favorite Ruth Ware book so far. My last two reads of hers were both good, but lacked great endings. This one remedies that, and the story on top of it was absolutely brilliant. I found myself wondering after every twist and turn what the truth of the story was, and when it was finally revealed, I was definitely satisfied.Side note, I've considered Ware's writing to be a modern Agatha Christie. Title: when
Author: daniel h. pink
review: Another great read by Daniel Pink. The idea that 'when' we do something differentiates 'how' we do it and 'how well' it goes is a concept we all underAnother great read by Daniel Pink. The idea that 'when' we do something differentiates 'how' we do it and 'how well' it goes is a concept we all understand, yet never really factor into account. This books does an excellent job of going over the topic, and shedding some light on a few specific examples of how that 'when' factor impacts the results most. Altogether, this book serves the purpose of spawning curiosity, and I look forward to reading some of the 'suggest reading' books included at the end....more

Title: educated
Author: tara westover
review: Another book I wasn't planning to finish so fast, but I just couldn't stop. Tara has lived an incredible life, whether she realized it or not during tAnother book I wasn't planning to finish so fast, but I just couldn't stop. Tara has lived an incredible life, whether she realized it or not during the events, because of her transformations and the trials that forced them. I truly didn't know what I was getting into when I started this book, but the gift of a story I've now read is more than I could have hoped. The power of education is truly incredible, but that's not necessarily this book's message. Dogmatic belief in anything can be dangerous, and more so when the believer is never exposed to dissenting views. That was Tara's life before school, and school, as well as the world, gave her the gift of that dissenting voice. It's not so much that Tara changed her views, but that the world gave her the opportunity to question those views for the first time. This was an incredible read, and I wish nothing but the best in life for the author....more

Title: everybody lies
Author: seth stephens-davidowitz
review: This is one of the coolest books I’ve ever listened to. Just like Freakonomics introduced us to a new way of seeing things using data, this book takesThis is one of the coolest books I’ve ever listened to. Just like Freakonomics introduced us to a new way of seeing things using data, this book takes some of the largest data sets ever in existence and lets them tell us story after story.The anecdotes are fascinating, but the real heart of this book is the how. How does Google search data lead to predicting voting patterns? How does word choice in books signify patriotism? These are the methodologies that can lead to so many insights about who we are, and it’s so exciting to see another author take the next step into this arena.For marketers, this should be required reading. Remember the Ford quote, and consider this glimpse into how data can be used to decode the enemy signals.Excellent read. Will definitely recommend forever....more

review: Ugh, I'm disappointed. 80% of this book was absolute gold (note the 4 stars). The book had an incredible Agatha Christie feel to it, reminding me a loUgh, I'm disappointed. 80% of this book was absolute gold (note the 4 stars). The book had an incredible Agatha Christie feel to it, reminding me a lot of Murder on the Orient Express. That was the thing I liked about the last Ruth Ware book I read. But then the plot just took an unexpected nose-dive, revealed the mystery with a huge chunk left, and just let the main character wallow in anguish while the plot unfolded outside of her scope. Plus, by the end, there's a lot of plotholes or storylines that go completely unresolved. The last 20% of this book was an absolute waste, and left a not-so-great taste in my mouth.Anyways, I still like Ware as an author, and this was actually more engaging than In a Dark, Dark Wood, but man, the ending is rough....more

review: This is a book about leadership, and from that standpoint, it's superb. The thought process is ethical and sound, and is a fantastic look into how a gThis is a book about leadership, and from that standpoint, it's superb. The thought process is ethical and sound, and is a fantastic look into how a great leader leads. While there's a great deal of politics involved, especially in the book's second half, looking past that to the book's core leaves a fantastic impression. As for the historical side, and the no-doubt anger in the books closing, it's an interesting look into one man's perspective. Title: such a fun age
Author: kiley reid
review: I don’t typically feel compelled to write reviews, especially bad ones but this is one of the worst books I’ve read in a long time. There is almost noI don’t typically feel compelled to write reviews, especially bad ones but this is one of the worst books I’ve read in a long time. There is almost no plot (literally NOTHING happens) and instead the entire premise focuses on the inner thoughts of and external relations between an employer and her nanny. The racial conversations were so continuous and overt and not from the perspective of the main character, which the book promises to be about. Show, don’t tell. Give the reader an interesting quandary to think about or create a situation that lets them think for themselves instead of regurgitating the same tired points.The most interesting part of the book is about 60-70% of the way through when the main character describes her inner conflict between how she feels about the job and where she feels she is supposed to be at her age. That’s what the book should have been about! This would have been a DNF for me if the audiobook didn’t have a good narrator, and it wasn’t so short....more

Whew it was ON POINT and months later I STILL remember the some of those scenes. The one critique I'd offer is that you really have to buy into traditional gender roles for this one. Title: daughter of the deep
Author: rick riordan
review: What a great concept for a middle grade novel. It's Hogwarts, but make it aquatic and instead of magic, make it high-tech! I will definitely be savingWhat a great concept for a middle grade novel. It's Hogwarts, but make it aquatic and instead of magic, make it high-tech! I will definitely be saving this to recommend to my kids when their reading level is appropriate. There is a strong female protagonist who shows bravery and great leadership. But it also shows the natural questioning of self and a lack of arrogance - very anti HBIC. The book also addresses how the MC's period affects her in her daily life - I'm sorry, what!? Normalize periods in kids books! And there is such a respectful treatment of an autistic character. Everyone is aware of her status, but it's just a natural thing to make a few accommodations for her. Her autism is treated more like a part of her personality and less like an illness that needs to be "cured."...more

review: I think this book is so important! I see the effort to make this material accessible for the younger reader and applaud those efforts! I really enjoyeI think this book is so important! I see the effort to make this material accessible for the younger reader and applaud those efforts! I really enjoyed learning more about historical context of events and the book overall. I did feel like the authorial voice was a tad heavy handed or almost preachy. I didn't disagree with the message, just wish it had been laid out as an argument while letting the reader see the validity without the authors having to essentially say: "see, it goes like this." That being said, perhaps that is just a condition of a non fiction book written for this audience group. I'm not well versed in the usual standard for those. I would still pick this up for teens in my life and I am considering reading the adult version to see if that "works" for me a little better....more

Title: caste
Author: isabel wilkerson
review: This was a certainly a revelatory read for me. I ended up documenting notes in my reading journal so that I could process the text and also to help meThis was a certainly a revelatory read for me. I ended up documenting notes in my reading journal so that I could process the text and also to help me remember to keep these concepts fresh in my mind.What this non fiction book does is to make it's point while still respecting the reader. It did NOT make me feel stupid for not having engaged in the thought regarding the subject matter. It did NOT beat me senseless over the head with the author's conclusions. Nor did it make me feel like a terrible person if I did not agree with every word of the text.It DID make the ideas/concepts accessible. It DID engage my brain with lovely allegories and metaphors to help me understand the author's point of view. It DID provide historical context to support that point of view. The prose was not heavy or dense and I really respect this author's work and extensive research. I had questions about some of her points and I felt there were some weaknesses in some of the chapters, but I still really respect Wilkerson's work. I found myself trying to start a conversation with anyone who would listen about the contents of the book and I think that is one of the author's main goal. To get people talking together and uncovering some of the "invisible" ways that race/caste impact our lives.I am considering reading the Warmth of Other Suns and look forward to her next project. I would recommend this book to people who: like non fiction, are hoping for something thought-provoking, and are open-minded....more

review: 3.5 starsUltimately, this book left me disappointed. I don't regret reading it, but I felt like it could have done so much more. The premise sounded s3.5 starsUltimately, this book left me disappointed. I don't regret reading it, but I felt like it could have done so much more. The premise sounded so interesting - paranormal-ish reimagining of the the voyage of the Donner Party. The subject matter was interesting enough to keep me engaged. By the end I had mostly figured out who people were, but it took me almost the whole book to figure out who belonged to which family and who was just a cattle hand/driver and how they were connected. I did enjoy that we got to see that(view spoiler)[many of these characters had hidden pasts.(hide spoiler)]There were certainly scenes that captured the horror - namely(view spoiler)[the scene with unknown sounds of BEINGS outside a tent full of family and children and the scene where a young man gets his ear ripped off.(hide spoiler)]However, it didn't really seem to do enough or the plot didn't resolve them spectacularly. I felt the emotion of the parents the most. Think of being out there in that wasteland and trying to figure out how to make sure your children survived. Shudder.For me, the ending was misleading based on information that we were given at the beginning of the book. We're told that(view spoiler)[there was only one survivor at the beginning of the book, but then the ending doesn't seem to match that.(hide spoiler)]There were also aspects of character developments/characteristics that didn't seem fully resolved to me. Why does Tamsen(view spoiler)[engage in a sexual relationship with Stanton? Is it just bc she is so unhappy? Was she just trying to get physical pleasure. The book made it seem like something was really going to come of this and then it seemed like when Stanton moved on with his new love interest, Mary Graves, nothing more seemed to come of their relationship...? /spoiler>In the end, it was just missing a little punch on the horror part and the cast of characters was pretty complicated. But, I did enjoy the overall idea of giving the historical happening a paranormal feel. I do appreciate all the research that the author did regarding the daily life and struggles of the pioneers.Also, I did minimum of research on the subject was pretty shocked to read that the rescue efforts carried almost as much peril as did the original journey! Title: when no one is watching
Author: alyssa cole
review: Read for Feb Literally Dead Book Club and March MomAdvice Book Club picks.Most underrated book! I do this this is perhaps mis-marketed as a "thriller.Read for Feb Literally Dead Book Club and March MomAdvice Book Club picks.Most underrated book! I do this this is perhaps mis-marketed as a "thriller." It doesn't have that instant gratification that most thrillers start out with some kind of punch like finding a body or a kidnapping scene or something of that nature. This is probably better classified as a horror book and the pacing is more reflective of that, in my opinion. Yes, the ending was a bit of a whirlwind, but I was fully captivated and on the edge of my seat!There is definitely a slow burn in the beginning of setting this really tense atmosphere and dropping these small bread crumbs of information about things that just don't "feel right." There is a scene with a young woman and a lyft/uber type of driver that is *cringe* so creepy.I didn't predict most of the twists at least to some extent. For example,(view spoiler)[I knew that there was something going on with Sydney's mom and that something was off there, but I never would have guessed that she died in her own home and then Sydney buried her in the community garden!DUDE.(hide spoiler)]Also, love all the social commentary on this book regarding racism and the interaction of community members and how what you say and do can really be impactful to those around you. Gentrification is a real issue and it's so complex and this just makes that topic more personalized and human. Perhaps it will open some eyes, as it did for me. Also think that is why this was so creepy for me bc it just didn't seem like much of a stretch for this to be happening! And it was so linked in to true history of the area that it doesn't take much to see how that really could happen. Obviously, it's fiction, but you get the idea.There was a great reading discussion video posted on BooksandLaLa's YT channel where some young women of color reflected on the book and certain scenes and I would highly recommend watching that after reading the book. Their perspectives were really enlightening for me!Now the one thing I could have done without is the fairly gratuitous sex scene, but listen. That's kind of a horror thing, right? If we consider this a horror and not a thriller, then maybe it's a little more justifiable why that scene is included. It's a Basic Instinct type of vibe. (Also, yes, that was Cole's main work prior to this novel - romance.) It didn't bother me over much....more

Title: the year of the witching
Author: alexis henderson
review: 3.5 starsI read this for the Fortnight Frights Readathon in Oct 2020.I wanted to like this book more than I did! I'm so disappointed - is it me or the3.5 starsI read this for the Fortnight Frights Readathon in Oct 2020.I wanted to like this book more than I did! I'm so disappointed - is it me or the book?! Other people seem to be madly in love, so it must be me. Honestly, I can't quite put my finger on why this book didn't quite work for me. I think possibly because I was expecting it to be more shocking? I'm not sure. What I do know is that for the majority of the time I was reading it, I felt just very blasé most times I picked it up.That being said, I think this book is doing important things. Here we have a character who is of mixed race -- born of a verboten relationship -- and she is choosing to disrupt the status quo in her community. She is a(view spoiler)[closeted reader -- women are not supposed to read anything other than the approved religious texts -- and she secretly appreciates the forbidden woods.(hide spoiler)]There is some interesting commentary (with only the thinnest of veils) about wealth and power and how that corresponds to color, gender, and community.Generally speaking, the plot did appeal to me and I felt it moved along at a good pace. I enjoyed many of the characters and the world seemed interesting. One of my favorite aspects of the novel was Emmanuelle's burgeoning relationship.Based on the premise, this should have been something I was fully immersed in, but somehow I just didn't experience that. But I think this is a really important book and makes that social commentary entertaining and accessible....more

Title: the guest list
Author: lucy foley
review: I'm giving this one 4.5 stars rounded up because I feel like the average rating for this right now (3.98) is too low!This is such an atmospheric storI'm giving this one 4.5 stars rounded up because I feel like the average rating for this right now (3.98) is too low!This is such an atmospheric story and has such a great setting! The scene setting and the characterization were amazing! This is being compared to the writings of Agatha Christie and I certainly understand that. Here we have a true mystery with suspense thrown in to up the ante.From the beginning, we are aware of a death, but we don't know who has died or the circumstances. Then we jump into chapters from our main characters, each being written from their POV. Now, I know some people don't like multiple POV and this one had several, but I did not mind it at all in this case. The characters were easily distinguishable for me and each added their own perspective and mood and important details that all combined to make a fab story. I loved that each chapter had some HINT of something ominous or mysterious. I absolutely turned aside other books that I was supposed to be reading for book clubs in order to read this. Definitely had that "un-put-down-able" quality.Now, I will say that around 40% complete I actually recorded a list of predictions about how the book would conclude and I would give myself a 65-70% accuracy rating with those. So, the story was just a hair predictable. HOWEVER, those predictions were in regards to the secrets each character carried and I definitely did not have a workable theory for what ACTUALLY HAPPENED AT THE WEDDING. So! For that reason, I only knocked off .5 a star. What a fun reading experience!...more

This book does completely have value and took a lot of bravery and emotional vulnerability for the author to write and is definitely worth a read....more

Title: the vanishing half
Author: brit bennett
review: I really enjoyed this book and I would recommend it to others. This is certainly a character and relationship driven book. The book focuses on twin siI really enjoyed this book and I would recommend it to others. This is certainly a character and relationship driven book. The book focuses on twin sisters and the way their paths in life diverge. Later in life, they each have have a daughter and you learn more about how those characters interact (or don't) as you follow the story.I really enjoyed the writing in this. It was engaging and descriptive, but without being overly flowery. I definitely felt like I had a connection to these characters and it was just fascinating to see how things developed. There is something so complex and sometimes almost...magical (?)...in the relationship between twins and also between mothers and daughters. There was also really interesting discussion of race and how that enters into our expectations, dreams/goals, and sense of self.One aspect of the book that I really enjoyed was the way that the name of the book was so meaningful to the story. I love it when authors choose a title that really has a connection to the story that isn't something super obvious.(view spoiler)[ As the story unfolds, I realized the "Vanishing Half" refers to the set of twin sisters breaking up and therefore losing their "other half - the vanishing half." And more than that, for Stella, when she chooses to pass in white society, she loses her Black identity and she becomes this split person who is hiding part of herself - her own "vanishing half." Furthermore, she inflicts that same vanishing on her daughter.(hide spoiler)]Overall, I would consider this an important book and I would certainly recommend it to others....more

Title: clap when you land
Author: elizabeth acevedo
review: 4.5 starsThis was a beautifully written novel. I have never read a modern story in verse like this. I didn't know what to expect with this type of nar4.5 starsThis was a beautifully written novel. I have never read a modern story in verse like this. I didn't know what to expect with this type of narration/this writing style and I was NOT disappointed. I loved how the verse itself changed structures - sometimes it rhymed, sometimes there was repetition, sometimes the phrases were long, sometimes short. I felt like that helped keep my interest. I also felt like the writing really helped convey the intention/mood of the characters - the audio narration was so good.For my rating on this book, I kept vacillating between four stars and five stars, so I settled on the 4.5 star rating. I just feel like this book is such an important representation of culture and the difficulties faced by teens. It's also a message about how powerful young women can be if they remain determined and how families can be so very complicated. I felt personally touched by these characters and found in this novel a lesson on empathy, on sensitivity, and awareness. Please read it!...more

Title: the house in the cerulean sea

review: Amazing, delightful, wonderful! Just what I wanted/needed to read during the crazy times we're having in the world right now (July 2020). This gave meAmazing, delightful, wonderful! Just what I wanted/needed to read during the crazy times we're having in the world right now (July 2020). This gave me HP + Miss Peregine's School for Peculiar Children vibes. I just loved the characters in this book, the tone of the writing, and the message. I actively WANTED to read it each time I picked it up and I was brought close to tears twice! (And books rarely make me cry!) It was just so lovely to read. The only nit picky thing I noticed was the lack of a cohesive time in the setting. The characters speak with a little bit of antiquated dialogue (think 50s) - it was charming, tho! - and some others with slang from the 70s. And then one character uses the computer and a credit card is "imprinted", but there's no cell phones, and music is played on records instead of the radio or a stereo. It was a little off and didn't quite match up. Ultimately, I don't even really CARE! STILL FIVE STARS!There was family, there was drama and prejudice, there was love, there was MAGIC. Title: a good girl's guide to murder
Author: holly jackson
review: Ultimately, this book was a lot of fun! I have to knock off one star for believability factor being low. But, honestly, that didn't lower my enjoymentUltimately, this book was a lot of fun! I have to knock off one star for believability factor being low. But, honestly, that didn't lower my enjoyment of this a super ton. Our protagonist, Pip, decides to do her senior capstone project on the disappearance of a young girl in her home town. Due to his general kindness toward her, she does not believe that the young man accused of the crime is guilty and she decides to investigate further. I thought it was cool how she saw an "every day" hero in him.I really enjoyed the two main characters, Pip and Ravi, the brother of the alleged criminal. They are just that brand of adorable awkward and still witty that is just the most fun to read. I really just let the story unfold without trying too TOO much to guess the perpetrator. The turn of events did get pretty thrilling and suspenseful. Definitely a rollercoaster ride.Now, the reason I knocked off one star. There were a few too many things I felt were holes in the novel. I mean, the whole concept that a teenager could uncover aspects of the crime that the police could not is one thing. But also(view spoiler)[ the motivation behind the crime was a bit weak bc Mr. Ward seemed to contradict himself about the repercussions of his crimes. The way her parents calmly accepted that she went to confront someone she suspected was a killer all on her own.She figures it out, GOES TO HIS HOUSE ALONE and they're just like...hmm...ok. Yep. No consequences and not even a discussion. And then she does it AGAIN when she knows there is more to the story and goes to confront another person and that just seems like SUCH a poor decision!(hide spoiler)]But these were balanced out by the overall exciting progress of the book and what I felt was a really good mystery. I also loved the(view spoiler)[speech that Pip gives at the end of the book which discussed how the community needs to do better so these terrible circumstances don't happen again. And also the great twists of a victim look alike and really TWO crimes being committed and TWO guilty parties! I didn't see that coming!(hide spoiler)]Highly recommend the audio book bc there are interviews with folks that relate to the events of the missing girl and the audio makes those very realistic....more

Title: the night swim
Author: megan goldin
review: I actually listened to this audio book during a road trip with my spouse (husband), who is not a voracious reader. He also rated it four stars. The boI actually listened to this audio book during a road trip with my spouse (husband), who is not a voracious reader. He also rated it four stars. The book held our attention throughout, for the most part, and also allowed for some really great discussion. We were both drawn in enough to offer our guesses about the plot and WHO is the guilty party in all the various crimes. We were definitely kept guessing and were not successful in guessing the final points until the very end of the story - just as it should be. We also really enjoyed the podcast sections of the book and felt like they meshed well with the overall story.This book facilitated some discussion between us about rape and assault and how women are affected. How people think of the victims and all they must endure both in their communities and legally. The trauma doesn't stop until long after the actual event/assault. As parents of a young girl, we could really relate to the characters of the victims parents, who were forced to decide how to approach her legal situation.Note for readers - in this novel, you're really following three timelines: the crime in the past that was committed against the "stalker's" sister, the podcaster's current day work to cover the rape trial for her listeners, and then the timeline of the trial's featured assault itself. So if you don't prefer multiple timelines, this may not be for you.In the end, we did knock off a star because the book did feel a bit long at some points and it was a bit difficult to keep all the various time frames straight. However, those were really pretty minor complaints. Would certainly recommend. Do be aware that there are graphic scenes and the subject matter is heavy....more

Title: in the dream house
Author: carmen maria machado
review: I am not going to enter a star rating on this one. The story is far too explicitly personal that it doesn't seem right to "rate" someone's actual lifeI am not going to enter a star rating on this one. The story is far too explicitly personal that it doesn't seem right to "rate" someone's actual life. I enjoyed the overall experience of this book and would recommend that others give it a try. The book certainly had the tone of one accustomed to academia and it is clear to me that the author conducted thorough research into the theme/topic in hopes of connecting her own experience with that of others. I enjoyed the "mental stimulation," if you will, of really reflecting on the allegories and folk tales presented throughout the book. I enjoyed how these were interwoven with the author's actual experience. I read the book both digitally and audibly and I would note that the audio book is a bit different. I do believe the author narrates the book and she had a different presentation than do many other audio books. The narration was read almost rhythmically or hypnotically and without much change in tone. The narration sounded the same when the author/narrator/protagonist was happy and when she was not. By the end, I'd become accustomed to it and it was sort of a soothing read, just maybe not something everyone would enjoy....more

Title: the ballad of songbirds and snakes
Author: suzanne collins
review: Listen, I just don't know how to rank this book. I'm conflicted. I'm going to go with four stars for now. This is a prequel for the Hunger Games storyListen, I just don't know how to rank this book. I'm conflicted. I'm going to go with four stars for now. This is a prequel for the Hunger Games story, but it's not your traditional origin story and it's different than Hunger Games (although it's been a long time since I read the series).What I liked:- Returning to the Hunger Games world- The perspective of someone who grew up in the Capital- Learning the history and how and why things from the Hunger Games came to be- The hints and references to the Hunger Games series- Meeting new characters and seeing how they fit into the world's history- Most of the plot/story line- The moral ambiguityWhat I didn't love:- The length (too long)- The rushed ending (I'm not a fan of epilogues just in general). The COMPLETE AND TOTAL 180 a character does in regards to another character just defies the entire 400 pages that came before. But then again, Snow struggles to define his own thoughts and theories throughout and I told you I was conflicted about the rating from the start, right?!- Just a bit too much philosophyI don't love the comment that this "didn't need to be written." Does ANY book need to be written? It's the author's choice and you either read it or don't depending on your interest level. If you didn't want to read a book about Snow, why did you? Sure, no one is loving this character, but that's not the point, in my opinion. Collins really seems to be trying to make a statement about humanity and morality and what power and corruption and greed can do to our humanity....more

Title: the southern book club's guide to slaying vampires
Author: grady hendrix
review: Listen. This is normally not my kind of book. I am not normally a horror kind of gal. But! This book was so hyped - I saw it mentioned many times in "Listen. This is normally not my kind of book. I am not normally a horror kind of gal. But! This book was so hyped - I saw it mentioned many times in "booklandia" and it caught my attention for the premise. Early 90s, housewives in the South, a book club, fighting vampires. Need I say more? And then I happened to see Grady Hendrix speaking on a panel for mystery/thriller/horror writers and I quite enjoyed his commentary. I just enjoyed is personality and his sensibilities. With that, I was sold and I went for it!This book quite delivered for me. Yes, there were heart racing moments, yes, there was gore and violence. But also a lovely sarcastic and humorous tone that really sets this book apart. I was getting the side eye for laughing aloud. Surprisingly, there were also a lot of themes woven into the story that were unexpected for me. Messages about women, their friendships, their connections with their spouses and/or children. Also thoughts on POC in the 90s in the South and their position in that community. I wasn't expecting to be so drawn into these friendships or find these characters so relatable.Absolutely recommend. For anyone who is not typically a horror reader and is worried about that content, I would say there are about 6-7 really graphic scenes and many other moments of suspense, fear, tension. I was able to handle these scenes, though one or two were right on the borderline of not being ok for me. Now to see if I can read any of the numerous book titles dropped throughout the book......more

Title: the only good indians
Author: stephen graham jones
review: 4.5 starsThis was such a thoughtful book. Yes, it's horror and it's thoughtful. Every piece of this work was carefully considered. Each scene moved t4.5 starsThis was such a thoughtful book. Yes, it's horror and it's thoughtful. Every piece of this work was carefully considered. Each scene moved the story inexorably forward to that breaking point in the plot - the point where everything comes to a head. The title of the book was purposeful, the chapter titles the same. The characters were fleshed out and well-developed. The themes were so powerful and far-reaching and the symbolism and story-telling devices were so well done.This is a horror novel, so let's not wax TOO poetic here. For me, the novel did not disappoint on the horror factor. There was gore, there was suspense, there was all those feelings of disquiet or "offness" that were SO effective. All of the horror seemed so BELEIVABLE for me, so it's no wonder I found myself shuddering and jumping at the slightest noises around me as I was reading (and listening).This book was written so well that the jumps in time frame did not bother me and I was able to keep the characters straight throughout. Every time I had to put this book down (damn you, work life and boo to these little humans taking up so much of my time!), I would look forward to picking it back up again.I have listened to and read several reviews and interviews with the author and with Native readers and it does seem that the representation is lauded and appreciated. Thank you, SGJ, for providing a window into the culture of of the reservation and into the thoughts and feelings of those Native folks from a reliable source. Also, I both read this book and listened to the audio book and I highly recommend the audio book too.The only reason that I docked a half a star was due to the basketball scenes in the novel. For me, these scenes became long, too complicated/technical, and repetitive. That being said, after some research and even while I was reading the novel, I understood that basketball is a very important part of reservation life for many people. So, while I still must account for my personal taste in writing a review and providing a star rating, I also understand the purpose for including the sport in the novel. I also understand that the(view spoiler)[basketball game at the end of the book really allows the author to portray the struggle that the characters are facing. As opposed to having a ton of internal dialogue for example, or a really long conversation that would spoil the momentum of the ending.(hide spoiler)]Overall, I would highly recommend this book to fans of horror. Title: my best friend's exorcism
Author: grady hendrix
review: What a ride it was to read this book! If you like 80s/90s nostalgia, high school girl friendships, and the nasty/disgusting type of horror, then thisWhat a ride it was to read this book! If you like 80s/90s nostalgia, high school girl friendships, and the nasty/disgusting type of horror, then this is the book for you! I enjoyed all the pop culture references, the friendships, the adventures. Also, this book has some great photos/graphics included! Don't miss those.As other reviewers have pointed out, this book does have a bit of a slow start in reference to the horror kicking in. However, as someone who is new to the genre and is is still somewhat intimidated by it and easily frightened, I didn't mind that at all. The beginning section of the book sets up the relationship between the two main characters and helps make the rest of the novel believable. It's what allows the reader to really feel the connection between and TO these characters, especially the MC, Abby.There are definitely some high-power (read gross) horror scenes, you just have to be a little patient for them.(view spoiler)[ There is a scene where a huge tape worm comes out of a young girl that is just BLRUG and another at the beginning of the book involving a naked teenage girl running through a dark wood and getting lost and finding a deserted shack that really spooked me too, among others.(hide spoiler)]I have a special affinity for this author as he weaves societal commentary into his stories and this one is no different. In this novel, there are instances where:(view spoiler)[1. a low income GIRL tries to alert various types of authorities that she believes her friend has been raped and no one listens to her, 2. the parents/school teachers are too offended by the scuffing of their sensibilities to listen to any kind of negative talk about the child of the school's wealthy donors, and 3. the underestimated (read marginalized) mother of a child speaks up and SHUTS down those trying to prevent her child from achieving success.(hide spoiler)]I loved the tenacity of Abby and her determination to do what's right, despite the huge obstacles in her path. I also did really enjoy the ending of the story.(view spoiler)[I loved the way that Hendrix portrays their friendship. That they go through periods of time where they're not that close or they don't speak as often (when everything is going well), but when the time comes and the need is there, they completely hold each other up and support each other.(hide spoiler)]That's real.Although I did really enjoy this one, I liked The Southern Book Club's Guide to Slaying Vampires better and so this one ended up at four stars. Would certainly still recommend it to others!...more

Title: beach read
Author: emily henry
review: So the premise of the book is just SO interesting and lured me in. A romance writer and a literary fiction writer both stuck in a rut/experiencing wriSo the premise of the book is just SO interesting and lured me in. A romance writer and a literary fiction writer both stuck in a rut/experiencing writer's block so they decide to switch genres and try writing again. Oh, and also these two have been rivals/competitive since college. What more do I need to say?! Also, I do enjoy a good book about books.I have heard it said that this is a book prolific romance readers will not love and new or limited romance readers will enjoy and I think that's probably accurate. It doesn't offer a cliched or overly raunchy relationship -- it's more raw and real than that. What I really enjoyed about this is that it really worked to turn those romance stereotypes around. I loved the "adorkable" scenes with our leading lady. She's not poised and elegant and sophisticated -- she's just trying her best to make it through and then she discovers her strength in the end. I want to hang out with her and best friend Shaddi. I loved the sense of humor throughout and the hate-to-love trope worked for me. I really think the overall tone of this is to show readers that you don't need to have roses and doves and sunsets to find love (but of course, they do help). :)I will say that the middle of the book did lag just a bit for me (thus knocking off a star), but the last quarter was just perfection for me, really. Loved the ending and the steamy bits were at just the right level to fit my preferences. If you're looking for a love story, but want to avoid the stereotypical romance, give this one a try....more

Title: autoboyography
Author: christina lauren
review: I feel like this story broke off a little piece of my heart. In the best way possible. These characters felt so REAL, so DEVELOPED, so...IMPORTANT. II feel like this story broke off a little piece of my heart. In the best way possible. These characters felt so REAL, so DEVELOPED, so...IMPORTANT. I had no idea before picking it up that this story would be connected to religion (my bad for not paying better attention to the blurb), but I was so pleasantly surprised by how it was handled. I don't feel like anyone from the church was demonized and Sebastian didn't lose his faith as he came to terms with his own longings, his own identity. I yearned for these two to be able to be happy together and I felt such a connection to them.I liked Tanner with his snarky, yet lovable remarks, his passion for his friends and family, and his willingness to really hope that the risks he's taking will all be worth it. And Sebastian. Sigh. I want to hold him and comfort him and tell him how worthwhile he is. The way the authors portrayed how his emotions and his faith warred with each other, yet also aligned, was just so beautiful.And let's talk about the real MVPs of this story - Tanner's parents!!! Mrs. and Mr. Scott, for the WIN! Can I get an AMEN?! In a way, I'm glad I read this as an adult, a parent. It really gives me insight into how my children or their friends may feel in the future. I can only hope that I can respond in the caring, protective, logical, supportive manner that portrayed in this novel.Please read this beautiful book....more

Title: the fifth season
Author: n.k. jemisin
review: Disclaimer about my rating on this one: I want to say to this book and this author - it's not you, it's me. I think this is a well written book and IDisclaimer about my rating on this one: I want to say to this book and this author - it's not you, it's me. I think this is a well written book and I can see its merits, however, I think it's just not to my taste. There was a time in my life where I was very into fantasy and might have dipped into sci fi...but this is not that time. I read this because it was selected as a book club pick and it's not something I would have gravitated towards otherwise. I think the writing was good and the characters were pretty interesting, but just the overall story line and/or subject just didn't strike me as engrossing.Positives:- The character growth. The three main POV were interesting and seemed mostly believable- Action scenes (limited). There were definitely some good action scenes (a pirate battle, yes!) and especially the last two chapters did capture my attention with their fast pace- The personal struggles of the characters. It was compelling what these folks had suffered at the hands of those in power and how that had shaped them- Increasing my diversity in authors and trying out a new authorNegatives:- The writing device that was used for the "big twist" or the final resolution.(view spoiler)[I personally just don't care for the device of OH BAM, all these characters are actually the same person! It feels like cheating or like the easy way out somehow.(hide spoiler)]- The ending. I understand this was just the first in the series, but I still feel like the ending fell flat(view spoiler)[ And I sort of despise an ending where the last thing we see is someone dying with so much unfinished business(hide spoiler)]- The technical aspects of the subject matter. Geology interests me very little and the descriptions of the tectonic plates and the types of Earth movements...yawn. I found all the magic that went with this boring, even though it was clear that was supposed to be one of the best bits- Being dropped into an unknown world with very little understanding of the setting. Much of the first quarter of the book involved being confused about what was where, what type of people were responsible for what, the different groups of characters/settings, etc...more

Title: the nightingale
Author: kristin hannah
review: 4.5 starsI had a bit of a mixed reaction to this book because I came to really enjoy the second half of the story more than the first and at times it4.5 starsI had a bit of a mixed reaction to this book because I came to really enjoy the second half of the story more than the first and at times it did seem overly long. I started out thinking the book was good, but over hyped. And then by the time I'd reached the end of the story, I'd developed a connection to these characters and their struggles and I had a more more emotional reaction than I did at the beginning. I finally settled at a 4.5 because I feel like this is a novel I'm going to remember for a long time.Personally, I feel like this may be the first (or one of very few at least) novel that I've read from the point of view of the people in Nazi-occupied France. So many of the novels that I've read in the past focus on British folks and their struggles, so this was a change of pace for me. This book certainly captured the deprivation, the hopelessness, and the constant anxiety and fear of the future that these people faced every day.I loved how the author based these stories around true acts of resistance during WWII. There really were people that(view spoiler)[hid Jewish children in "plain sight" and falsified documents and reports in order to protect them. And there actually was a young girl who took downed Allied airmen through the mountains to safety.(hide spoiler)]It's amazing to me what people will do to protect those in need - heroes all.The writing here was so lovely. Not overly flowery or pretentious, but still very evocative of the setting and especially the emotions of the characters. They felt very real to me as I was reading. I especially identified with the older sister in the story as a mother. The story line moved along pretty quickly after the first say 25% ish of the book.And I really enjoyed the moral ambiguity of the characters throughout. That's reality. It's not always so clear cut about who are "good guys" who are "bad guys" and that really worked for me in this book.(view spoiler)[ Not every German soldier behaved like a rabid animal and not every French citizen acted heroically to save their countrymen/people. In the case of the first German that was billeted with the family in the countryside, our MC almost had a romantic relationship there - with the enemy - because the world was so harsh and she was so scared and he was kind - as kind as he could be - to her. And yet he betrayed her by making her write the list of Jewish and communist townspeople and in the end, she ended up betraying him by killing him. Who was right? Who was wrong?(hide spoiler)]Love a book that fosters those kind of discussions.I did feel like the romance element of the book was a little stilted and a little awkward in the first part of the book. Although it still didn't feel like the best romantic portrayal (a bit far-fetched), by the end, I was rooting for them to be able to be together. The romance was not a super central aspect of the story, so it was pretty easy to sort of overlook my objections there.In the end, I would certainly recommend this book!...more

Title: what the wind knows
Author: amy harmon
review: This is the first book by Amy Harmon that I've read and I think I would give her others a try. Overall, I was happy that I read this one and quite enjThis is the first book by Amy Harmon that I've read and I think I would give her others a try. Overall, I was happy that I read this one and quite enjoyed the experience.What I loved:- The setting and the atmosphere: beautiful portrayal of both the current and historical scenes in Ireland. Definitely set a mood and a tone and made me want to visit.- The romance: just beautiful writing about love and what it's like to love another so purely and with such consuming passion, but without feeling trite or contrived.- The melding of fictional and historical characters and events: I so enjoyed "getting to know" the characters, both fictional and historical. Prompted me to do some further research.- The plot: the details slowly came together to form the final picture and I appreciate how that all culminated, with one or two small objections. I certainly liked more of the plot and only had a few minor questions.What I didn't love (and why I knocked off a star):- A plot hole: I don't want to spoil the ending, so being vague...I couldn't understand why one of the characters didn't try to undo something that had happened. At the end, I saw why she couldn't or at least why it couldn't have been successful, but it seemed unrealistic for her not to at least attempt it.- Je ne sais quoi: while I really enjoyed it, there was just that last little something missing to make me push this into the five star category. Would definitely recommend, however....more

Title: where the crawdads sing
Author: delia owens
review: 4.5 stars.This was a really interesting concept - not one I think I've read before. The story starts off as a "coming of age" tale as we follow a youn4.5 stars.This was a really interesting concept - not one I think I've read before. The story starts off as a "coming of age" tale as we follow a young girl living alone (or mostly alone) in a North Carolina marsh. But from the beginning, we know there is also a murder mystery occurring. The story moves slowly at first, but I felt the languorous pace really evoked the natural setting of the marsh and the gently flowing estuaries that our main character so adores. However, the last third of the book moved quickly as we go through a murder trial. Overall, I very much enjoyed this book and would recommend. I did knock off .5 of a star because of the ending. I had a different idea of how I thought the book should conclude, but I didn't hate the way the author chose to go.There are definitely themes of feminism, what happens to the "less than" in society, and the power of self-preservation woven throughout the story. Many times, after finishing a book, I move right on to the next one (even for really great stories). But this one has me thinking and not yet ready to move on. All the great reviews you'll read are not wrong!...more

Title: the fault in our stars
Author: john green
review: The Fault in Our Stars is one of those books that leaves you feeling lots of emotions—love, pain, hope, and heartbreak. It ain’t just a story about twThe Fault in Our Stars is one of those books that leaves you feeling lots of emotions—love, pain, hope, and heartbreak. It ain’t just a story about two teens with cancer. It’s about finding a will to live when you’ve accepted death, falling in love when you least expect it, and realizing how life can be beautiful.Hazel Grace and Augustus Waters are both living with the weight of illness, but they are so much more than just patients. Hazel is quiet, almost scared of getting too close to people so she won’t hurt them by dying. Augustus, however, is full of life despite his vulnerability and the challenges he’s learned to live with. When they meet, it’s like their lives aren’t empty anymore.Their bond isn’t cheesy or perfect like in movies. It’s honest, raw, and filled with vulnerability, the kind of love that is both exciting and terrifying. I could almost feel the emotions. Their talks, laughs, and cries were so beautiful yet heart-wrenching.Reading it makes us understand that life isn’t always a fairy tale. This book makes us appreciate the small moments—short conversations, shared glances, and content silence. The way Augustus cried and expressed his emotions while Hazel lay dead, and how he got himself together, would cause one’s heart to shatter.John Green didn’t sugarcoat anything. He tells how painful it can be to love someone who you know will leave someday, but also how worth it love can be. The ending broke me, but also taught me that love isn’t always sunshines and rainbows. In fact, it can be painful and raw. Love is pain, but it can change everything.I personally would rate this book a 5 out of 5 because of how beautifully it’s written. It’s not just a love story—it’s a life story....more

Tris's mother must have changed his surname after marrying Andrew Prior, So Edith Prior must be an Erudite if she is mother of Andrew Prior .. well time to find out..Time forALLEGIANT....more

Title: verity
Author: colleen hoover
review: **spoiler alert** While this book was a quick, entertaining read, it just felt like not enough actually happens and then the resolution of everything**spoiler alert** While this book was a quick, entertaining read, it just felt like not enough actually happens and then the resolution of everything at the end was just too much. I already didn't really buy the instant attraction of the main characters and their cavalier affair. Too much just falls into place. But seriously, to have the wife FAKING a semi-vegetative state for months? Puh-lease. That's just ridiculous. She has doctors and professional nurses and she somehow never ever flinches and messes up? And she's talking to her kid? And the whole trope where she just can't find a way to tell Jeremy her manuscript is fake? Really? She was in the hospital before coming home and she couldn't find a safe space to wake up and tell a doctor or a nurse or a therapist what happened? Instead she made this magic plan to go home and pretend to be a vegetable for months and then steal her kid? Because the doctors wouldn't believe her over this manuscript? I just can't. And how stupid Lowen is to just not care about getting pregnant from a guy she's known for a couple weeks? The whole plot is that she's ghost writing these novels and the whole books spends nary a page talking about her actually working on the books she's being paid to write. This just fell flat after it was over and I was able to digest all the problems with the plot....more

review: Ugh, this book had so many problems. First, it was WAY TOO LONG. It just kept going and going and going. Second, it was just over the top on trying toUgh, this book had so many problems. First, it was WAY TOO LONG. It just kept going and going and going. Second, it was just over the top on trying to make the main character's life as hellish as possible. At some point, as you hear the horrid things that happened to him, you just start to roll your eyes and think puh-lease. Just one of the many terrifying situations he was in would be enough. And then to have him be a highly intelligent, educated, accomplished man, who everyone just treats with kid gloves and forgives him no matter what he does to himself, but never actually push him to find a way to love himself. It just was all too maudlin, too over the top. At some point not even halfway into the book, I really started hoping he maybe would just die and we could just read about the other characters. Ugh....more

review: I liked this book a lot because of the first-hand accounts of historical events that touched so many lives. At the same time, sometimes it feels almosI liked this book a lot because of the first-hand accounts of historical events that touched so many lives. At the same time, sometimes it feels almost forced or too convenient that these invented characters just happen to be right-hand men of famous historical figures. I would have been just as happy to see these historical events through everyday people's lives rather than people who work in the White House or Kremlin, etc. I found the most touching story lines to be the ones of everyday people who experience the world around them instead of the powerful people. Overall, I really did enjoy reading the book and jumping around geographically to see different people's lives. I've read every Ken Follett book he's written and I will continue to do so!...more

review: I had fairly high hopes for this book but was left terribly disappointed. The writing itself was generally lovely and well done, although there were iI had fairly high hopes for this book but was left terribly disappointed. The writing itself was generally lovely and well done, although there were instances of overly-descriptive passages that became bogged down in unnecessary details. I found the fables intriguing and at points gripping, but felt that the nuanced meaning behind these stories/myths could have been better incorporated into the main story (rather than a weak attempt to suddenly explain everything in the last 5 pages). My main criticism is that the book as a whole fell flat; the main characters lacked dynamism and Natalia's reaction and emotions in response to her grandfather's death were unconvincing.An interesting concept for a novel that I hoped would be more profound and revelatory but it just didn't quite work for me and left me wondering what was the point of it all....more
